# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: london
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:london/020] The 020 area code fully replaced older area codes for London on 22 April 2000, following multiple telephone number changes during the 1990s.
[src:london/020] As is the case for other codes in the UK, the 020 area code may also be used for services without any physical presence in the area, such as private networks or virtual numbering.
[src:london/020] One such user is the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Telecommunications Network, provided by Global Crossing, 020 is also one of the dialling codes used for telephone services on the remote South Atlantic island of Tristan da Cunha.
[src:london/020] Before the introduction of national dialling codes, the area now served by 020 had a large multiple telephone exchange system, called the London telephone area.
[src:london/020] The first exchange in this area, Central, was opened in the City of London on 1 March 1902.
[src:london/020] The Director telephone system was developed so that subscribers in London could call one another in a linked numbering scheme regardless of whether they were on a manual local exchange or an automatic one.
[src:london/020] In 1927, Holborn, the first Director automatic exchange in London, was cut over to the new system at midnight on Saturday 12 November.
[src:london/020] Because it was mainly a business exchange, most subscribers did not use the new system until Monday 14 November.
[src:london/020] The successful changeover was delayed by subscribers' unfamiliarity with dialling.
[src:london/020] Bishopgate and Sloane exchanges followed in six weeks, after which came Western and Monument exchanges.
[src:london/020] Because the London area contained 80 exchanges, complete conversion took many years.
[src:london/020] By 1934, the London telephone area comprised all 147 exchanges within 12+1⁄2 miles (20 km) of Oxford Circus.
[src:london/020] By 1950, the London Director system had 75 exchanges within a 5-mile (8 km) radius of Oxford Circus and a further 65 in the 5–10-mile (8–16 km) belt.
[src:london/020] In Greater London (in other words, within 20 miles (32 km) of Oxford Circus), there were 237 exchanges.
[src:london/020] In January 1956 a new director exchange – "SKYport" – was opened at London Heathrow Airport.
[src:london/020] From 1922, the first three digits of a seven-digit subscriber number – in other words, the local exchange codes – were represented with letters by way of a mnemonic.
[src:london/020] Each three-character code corresponded to an exchange within the London telephone area.
[src:london/020] The subscriber numbers were written, for example, as "ABBey 1234" and "WIMbledon 1234" or "ABB 1234" and "WIM 1234".
[src:london/020] By 1965, there were 350 local exchanges in London and the number of permutations that could be used for exchange names had been exhausted.
[src:london/020] With the change to all-figure dialling in 1966, the system of mnemonics was withdrawn and the three-digit local exchange codes of many subscribers were altered.
[src:london/020] The old codes continued to work in parallel with new codes until January 1970, when the "ANN: All-figure Numbers Now" advertising campaign prompted callers to use only the new codes.
[src:london/020] The transition to all-figure dialling allowed the codes to be grouped into eight sectors; all exchanges within 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) of the centre of London formed the Central sector and the other sectors radiated from it.
[src:london/020] The first three digits of a subscriber number continued to indicate the exchange to which the number belonged; for example, "222 1234" was in Westminster (Central Sector) and "946 1234" in Wimbledon (South West Sector).
[src:london/020] More than one local exchange code was usually overlaid for each area, so all Wimbledon numbers did not necessarily begin "946".
[src:london/020] Subscriber numbers changed to eight digits in 2000 when an additional 7 or 8 was added to each local exchange code (for example, "7222 1234" in Westminster and "8946 1234" in Wimbledon).
[src:london/020] The STD code 01 was assigned to the London telephone area on 6 April 1959 as part of preparations for subscriber trunk dialling.
[src:london/020] For the next thirty years, "01" became synonymous with the capital.
[src:london/020] Until May 1990, the 01 code covered the same area as the current 020 code and had capacity for fewer than 10 million telephone numbers.
[src:london/020] In May 1990, the 01 code was abandoned and the area divided between 071 – which covered exchanges in the Central sector – and 081, which covered all other sectors.
[src:london/020] Exceptionally, two exchanges in the East sector covering the London Docklands redevelopment area were assigned the 071 code.
[src:london/020] The anticipation that the code associated with central districts would be more prestigious than the other associated with the outer suburbs was used as a plot device in the Essex-based TV comedy series *Birds of a Feather*.
[src:london/020] At the time of the split, there were five local exchange codes assigned to Mercury Communications and numbers in these ranges could be assigned to either code.
[src:london/020] This area code split doubled the potential capacity.
[src:london/020] In 1995, on "PhONEday", the codes changed again, to 0171 and 0181.
[src:london/020] The split into two area codes only lasted a decade.
[src:london/020] As part of the Big Number Change on 22 April 2000, the 0171 and 0181 codes were replaced with 020, following a period of dual-running that began on 1 June 1999 when the new 020 code was activated and ended on 14 October 2000 when the old 0171 and 0181 codes were finally ceased.
[src:london/020] The 22 April 2000 change also affected subscriber local numbers which gained an extra digit.
[src:london/020] As a result of this history, there is now a widespread misconception that 0207 and 0208 are the dialling codes for parts of London.
[src:london/020] This was exacerbated when local numbers beginning 3 started to be issued.
[src:london/020] The reunification under a single code created capacity for approaching 100 million telephone numbers and, starting in 2005, subscriber numbers beginning with the digit "3" were issued alongside those beginning "7" and "8".
[src:london/020] In August 2019, Ofcom announced that subscriber numbers beginning with the digit "4" will also be introduced.
[src:london/020] The London telephone area operated as a single group for charging purposes in which all calls were priced at local rate.
[src:london/020] Additionally, as was usual, calls to and from the adjacent charge groups were charged as local.
[src:london/020] The code serves a roughly circular area with a radius of 12 miles from the centre of London.
[src:london/020] The Greater London boundary varies from 11 miles to 20 miles from the centre and consequently some outer districts are covered by adjacent codes and in some places the 020 code extends beyond the Greater London boundary.
[src:london/020] The code covers an area larger than the London post town where letters addressed to "LONDON" are delivered.
[src:london/020] The City of London and at least some part of all 32 London boroughs are within the 020 area code.
[src:london/020] There are six exchanges outside Greater London that use the 020 code.
[src:london/020] Communities outside Greater London that are within the code are Buckhurst Hill, Chigwell, Loughton and Sewardstone in Essex; Borehamwood, Bushey, Carpenders Park, Elstree and South Oxhey in Hertfordshire; and Ewell, Molesey, Thames Ditton and Whyteleafe in Surrey.
[src:london/020] There are eighteen exchanges within Greater London that do not use the 020 code.
[src:london/020] With the introduction of the (020) area code, as part of the Big Number Change, subscriber numbers were changed from 7-digits (xxx xxxx) to 8-digits (xxxx xxxx).
[src:london/020] This allowed new ranges of numbers to be issued.
[src:london/020] In 2006 59% of numbers within the 020 code were allocated to BT.
[src:london/020] The area code is not subject to number conservation and the regulator Ofcom does not restrict the size of number blocks that are allocated.
[src:london/1-000-000-000] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:london/1-000-000-000] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:london/1-000-000-000] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:london/1-000-000-000] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:london/1-000-000-000] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:london/1-000-000-000] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:london/1-000-000-000] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:london/1-000-000-000] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It is over 300 years old, is a Grade I listed building, and contains approximately 100 rooms.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A private residence for the prime minister occupies the third floor and there is a kitchen in the basement.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The other floors contain offices and conference, reception, sitting and dining rooms where the prime minister works, and where government ministers, national leaders, and foreign dignitaries are met and hosted.
[src:london/10-downing-street] At the rear is an interior courtyard and a terrace overlooking a 1⁄2-acre (0.2 ha) garden.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Number 10 is adjacent to St James's Park, approximately 3⁄4 mile (1.2 km) from Buckingham Palace, the official residence of the British monarch in London, and is near the Palace of Westminster, the meeting place of both Houses of Parliament.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Originally three houses, Number 10 was offered to Robert Walpole by King George II in 1732.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Walpole accepted on the condition that the gift was to the office of First Lord of the Treasury.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The post of First Lord of the Treasury has, for much of the 18th and 19th centuries and invariably since 1905, been held by the prime minister.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Walpole commissioned William Kent to join the three houses and it is this larger house that is known as Number 10 Downing Street.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Despite its size and convenient location near to Parliament, few early prime ministers lived at 10 Downing Street.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Costly to maintain, neglected, and run-down, Number 10 was scheduled to be demolished several times, but the property survived and became linked with many statesmen and events in British history.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1985 Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Number 10 had become "one of the most precious jewels in the national heritage".
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Prime Minister's Office, for which the terms *Downing Street* and *Number 10* are metonyms, lies within the 10 Downing Street building and is part of the Cabinet Office.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It is staffed by civil servants and special advisers.
[src:london/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street is property of His Majesty's Government.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Its registered legal title is held in the name of the secretary of state for housing, communities and local government, and the secretary of state is a corporation sole.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Number 10 Downing Street was originally three properties: a mansion overlooking St James's Park called "the House at the Back", a town house behind it, and a cottage.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The town house, from which the modern building gets its name, was one of several built by Sir George Downing, 1st Baronet between 1682 and 1684.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Downing, a noted spy for Oliver Cromwell and later King Charles II, invested in property and acquired considerable wealth.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1654, he purchased the lease on land south of St James's Park, adjacent to the House at the Back within walking distance of parliament.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Downing planned to build a row of terraced town houses "for persons of good quality to inhabit in ..." The street on which he built them now bears his name, and the largest became part of Number 10 Downing Street.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Straightforward as the investment seemed, it proved otherwise.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Hampden family had a lease on the land that they refused to relinquish.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Downing fought their claim, but failed and had to wait 30 years before he could build.
[src:london/10-downing-street] When the Hampden lease expired, Downing received permission to build on land further west to take advantage of more recent property developments.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The new warrant issued in 1682 reads: "Sir George Downing ... [is authorised] to build new and more houses ... subject to the proviso that it be not built any nearer than 14 feet of the wall of the said Park at the West end thereof".
[src:london/10-downing-street] Between 1682 and 1684, Downing built a cul-de-sac of two-storey town houses with coach-houses, stables and views of St James's Park.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Over the years, the addresses changed several times.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Downing employed Christopher Wren to design the houses.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Although large, they were put up quickly and cheaply on soft soil with shallow foundations.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Winston Churchill wrote that Number 10 was "shaky and lightly built by the profiteering contractor whose name they bear".
[src:london/10-downing-street] The upper end of the Downing Street cul-de-sac closed off the access to St James's Park, making the street quiet and private.
[src:london/10-downing-street] An advertisement in 1720 described it as "a pretty open Place, especially at the upper end, where are four or five very large and well-built Houses, fit for Persons of Honour and Quality; each House having a pleasant Prospect into St James's Park, with a Tarras Walk".
[src:london/10-downing-street] The cul-de-sac had several distinguished residents: George Granville, 1st Baron Lansdowne from 1692 to 1696 and the Earl of Grantham from 1699 to 1703.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1675, he retired to Cambridge, where he died in 1684, a few months after building was completed.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1800, the wealth he had accumulated was used to found Downing College, Cambridge, as had been his wish should his descendants fail in the male line.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Downing's portrait hangs in the entrance hall of Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The "House at the Back", the largest of the three houses which were combined to make Number 10, was a mansion built in about 1530 next to the Palace of Whitehall.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Rebuilt, expanded, and renovated many times since, it was originally one of several buildings that made up the "Cockpit Lodgings", so-called because they were attached to an octagonal structure used for cock-fighting.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Early in the 17th century, the Cockpit was converted to a concert hall and theatre; after the Glorious Revolution of 1688, some of the first cabinet meetings were held there secretly.
[src:london/10-downing-street] For many years, the "House at the Back" was the home of Thomas Knyvet, Keeper of Whitehall Palace, famous for capturing Guy Fawkes in 1605 and foiling his plot to assassinate King James I.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The previous year, Knyvet had moved into a house next door, approximately where Number 10 is today.
[src:london/10-downing-street] From that time, the "House at the Back" was usually occupied by members of the royal family or the government.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Princess Elizabeth, eldest daughter of King James I, lived there from 1604 until 1613 when she married Frederick V, Elector Palatine and moved to Heidelberg.
[src:london/10-downing-street] She was the grandmother of King George I, the Elector of Hanover, who became King of Great Britain in 1714, and was a great-grandmother of King George II, who presented the house to Walpole in 1732.
[src:london/10-downing-street] George Monck, 1st Duke of Albemarle, the general responsible for the Restoration of the Monarchy in 1660, lived there from 1660 until his death in 1671.
[src:london/10-downing-street] As head of the Great Treasury Commission of 1667–1672, Albemarle transformed accounting methods and allowed the Crown greater control over expenses.
[src:london/10-downing-street] His secretary, George Downing, who built Downing Street, is thought to have created these changes.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Albemarle is the first treasury minister to have lived in what became the home of the First Lord of the Treasury and prime minister.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1671, George Villiers, 2nd Duke of Buckingham took possession when he joined the Cabal Ministry.
[src:london/10-downing-street] At considerable expense, Buckingham rebuilt the house.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The result was a spacious mansion, lying parallel to Whitehall Palace with a view of St James Park from its garden.
[src:london/10-downing-street] After Buckingham retired in 1676, Lady Charlotte Fitzroy, Charles II's daughter, moved in when she married Edward Lee, 1st Earl of Lichfield.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Crown authorised extensive rebuilding which included adding a storey, thus giving it three main floors, an attic and basement.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This structure can be seen today as the rear section of Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] *(See Plan of the Premises Granted to the Earl and Countess of Lichfield in 1677)* The likely reason that repair was required is that the house had settled in the swampy ground near the Thames, causing structural damage.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Like Downing Street, it rested on a shallow foundation, a design error that caused problems until 1960 when the modern Number 10 was rebuilt on deep pilings.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Lichfields followed James II into exile after the Glorious Revolution.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Two years later in 1690, William III and Mary II gave the "House at the Back" to Hendrik van Nassau-Ouwerkerk, a Dutch general who had assisted in securing the Crown for the Prince of Orange.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Nassau, who Anglicised his name to "Overkirk", lived there until his death in 1708.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The "House at the Back" reverted to the Crown when Lady Overkirk died in 1720.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Treasury issued an order "for repairing and fitting it up in the best and most substantial manner" at a cost of £2,522.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The name of the "House at the Back" changed with the occupant, from Lichfield House to Overkirk House in 1690 to Bothmer House in 1720.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Johann Caspar von Bothmer, Premier Minister of the Electorate of Hanover, head of the German Chancery and adviser to George I and II, took up residency in 1720.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Although Bothmer complained about "the ruinous Condition of the Premises", he lived there until his death in 1732.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Even though Count von Bothmer was not British, he was a subject of George I and George II and the first politician and head of a government who resided in 10 Downing Street.
[src:london/10-downing-street] When Count Bothmer died, ownership of the "House at the Back" reverted to the Crown.
[src:london/10-downing-street] George II took this opportunity to offer it to Robert Walpole, often called the first prime minister, as a gift for his services to the nation: stabilising its finances, keeping it at peace and securing the Hanoverian succession.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Walpole did not accept the gift for himself.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He proposed – and the King agreed – that the Crown give the properties to the Office of First Lord of the Treasury.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Walpole would live there as the incumbent First Lord, but would vacate it for the next one.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To enlarge the new house, Walpole persuaded one *Mr.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Chicken*, the tenant of a cottage next door, to move to another house in Downing Street.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This small house and the mansion at the back were then incorporated into Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Walpole commissioned William Kent to convert them into one building.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Kent joined the larger houses by building a two-storey structure between them, consisting of one long room on the ground floor and several above.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The remaining interior space was converted into a courtyard.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He connected the Downing Street houses with a corridor.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Having united the structures, Kent gutted and rebuilt the interior.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He then surmounted the third storey of the house at the back with a pediment.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To allow Walpole quicker access to Parliament, Kent closed the north side entrance from St James's Park, and made the door in Downing Street the main entrance.
[src:london/10-downing-street] On 23 September 1735, the *London Daily Post* announced that: "Yesterday the Right Hon.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Sir Robert Walpole, with his Lady and Family, removed from their House in St James's Square, to his new House, adjoining to the Treasury in St James's Park".
[src:london/10-downing-street] Originally estimated at £8,000, the final cost probably exceeded £20,000.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Walpole did not enter through the now-famous door; that would not be installed until forty years later.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Kent's door was modest, belying the spacious elegance beyond.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The First Lord's new, albeit temporary, home had sixty rooms, with hardwood and marble floors, cornices, elegant pillars and marble mantelpieces; those on the west side with views of St James's Park.
[src:london/10-downing-street] One of the largest rooms was a study measuring forty feet by twenty with enormous windows overlooking St James's Park.
[src:london/10-downing-street] "My Lord's Study" (as Kent labelled it in his drawings) would later become the Cabinet Room where prime ministers meet with the Cabinet ministers.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Shortly after moving in, Walpole ordered that a portion of the land outside his study be converted into a terrace and garden.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The same document confirmed that Number 10 Downing Street was: "meant to be annexed & united to the Office of his Majesty's Treasury & to be & to remain for the Use & Habitation of the first Commissioner of his Majesty's Treasury for the time being".
[src:london/10-downing-street] At about the same time that William Kent was combining the Downing Street townhouse with the house at the back, he was also commissioned to design and construct a new Treasury building on the site of the old Tudor Cockpit located behind Downing Street.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This project was completed in 1737 and included corridors connecting the Treasury building with 10 Downing Street allowing Walpole, as Chancellor of the Exchequer as well as First Lord of the Treasury, direct and convenient access to the Treasury offices.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In effect the Treasury building became an annex of 10 Downing Street and its staff worked directly for Walpole on treasury, patronage and other public business.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This arrangement remained in effect until the middle of the 19th century and until then all prime ministers who were also Chancellor took advantage of it.
[src:london/10-downing-street] After Prime Minister Robert Peel "gave up" being Chancellor in 1841, and this separation of positions gradually became a convention of the constitution, a locked door was installed between the buildings limiting the Prime Minister's access to the Treasury and its staff.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Due to bomb damage in 1940, the Treasury relocated to the Government Offices Great George Street.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Then in 1963 the Cabinet Office (including the Prime Minister's Office) and later the Civil Service (with the Prime minister as Minister for the Civil Service) moved into the renovated Kent Treasury Building.
[src:london/10-downing-street] "Under (Prime Minister) Blair . . . the locked door, symbolically and physically dividing No.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Although he had accepted it on behalf of future First Lords of the Treasury, it would be 21 years before any of his successors chose to live there; the five who followed Walpole preferred their own homes.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This was the pattern until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Of the 31 First Lords from 1735 to 1902, only 16 (including Walpole) lived in Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] One reason many First Lords chose not to live in Number 10 was that most of them owned London town houses that were superior in size and quality.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Their possession of the house, albeit temporary, was a perquisite they could bestow as a political reward.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Most lent it to the Chancellor of the Exchequer, others to lesser officials or to friends and relatives.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Another reason for its unpopularity was that Number 10 was a hazardous place in which to live; it was prone to sinking because it was built on soft soil and a shallow foundation, and its floors buckled and walls and chimneys cracked.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It became unsafe and frequently required repairs.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1766, for example, Charles Townshend, Chancellor of the Exchequer, pointed out that the house was in a dilapidated condition.
[src:london/10-downing-street] His architect's letter to the Treasury stated: "...we have caused the House in Downing Street belonging to the Treasury to be surveyed, & find the Walls of the old part of the said House next the street to be much decayed, the Floors & Chimneys much sunk from the level".
[src:london/10-downing-street] Townshend ordered extensive repairs, which were still incomplete eight years later.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A note from Lord North to the Office of Works, dated September 1774, asks for the work on the front of the house, "which was begun by a Warrant from the Treasury dated 9 August 1766", to be finished.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Treasury officials complained that the building was costing too much to maintain; some suggested that it should be razed and a new house constructed on the site or elsewhere.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1782 the Board of Works reporting on "the dangerous state of the old part of the House", stated that "no time be lost in taking down said building".
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1783 the Duke of Portland moved out because it was once again in need of repair.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A committee found that the money spent so far was insufficient.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This time the Board of Works declared that "the Repairs, Alterations & Additions at the Chancellor of the Exchequer's House will amount to the sum of £5,580, exclusive of the sum for which they already have His Majesty's Warrant.
[src:london/10-downing-street] And praying a Warrant for the said sum of £5,580 – and also praying an Imprest of that sum to enable them to pay the Workmen".
[src:london/10-downing-street] This proved to be a gross underestimate; the final bill was over £11,000.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A few prime ministers however did enjoy living in Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Lord North, who conducted the war against the American Revolution, lived there happily with his family from 1767 to 1782.
[src:london/10-downing-street] William Pitt the Younger, who made it his home for twenty years (longer than any First Lord before or since) from 1783 to 1801 and from 1804 to 1806, referred to it as "My vast, awkward house".
[src:london/10-downing-street] While there, Pitt reduced the national debt, formed the Triple Alliance against France and won passage of the Act of Union that created the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Robinson, 1st Viscount Goderich, took a special liking to the house in the late 1820s and spent state funds lavishly remodelling the interior.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Nevertheless, for 70 years following Pitt's death in 1806, Number 10 was rarely used as the First Lord's residence.
[src:london/10-downing-street] From 1834 to 1877, it was either vacant or used only for offices and meetings.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Downing Street declined at the turn of the 19th century, becoming surrounded with run-down buildings, dark alleys, the scene of crime and prostitution.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Earlier, the government had taken over the other Downing Street houses: the Colonial Office occupied Number 14 in 1798; the Foreign Office was at Number 16 and the houses on either side; the West India Department was in Number 18; and the Tithe Commissioners in Number 20.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The houses deteriorated from neglect, became unsafe, and one by one were demolished.
[src:london/10-downing-street] By 1857 Downing Street's townhouses were all gone except for Number 10, Number 11 (customarily the Chancellor of the Exchequer's residence), and Number 12 (used as offices for Government Whips).
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1879 a fire destroyed the upper floors of Number 12; it was renovated but only as a single-storey structure.
[src:london/10-downing-street] When Lord Salisbury retired in 1902, his nephew, Arthur James Balfour, became prime minister.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It was an easy transition: he was already First Lord of the Treasury and he was already living in Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Balfour revived the custom that Number 10 is the First Lord and Prime Minister's official residence.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Without a bomb shelter, during World War II the Prime Minister abandoned Number 10 instead using a flat in the Foreign office that became known as the No.10 Annexe, and lay above the much more comprehensive underground bunker used by Winston Churchill and now known as the Churchill War Rooms.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To reassure the people that his government was functioning normally, he insisted on being seen entering and leaving Number 10 occasionally, and indeed, continued to use it for meetings and dinners despite being urged not to.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Harold Wilson, during his second ministry from 1974 to 1976, lived in his home in Lord North Street because Mary Wilson wanted "a proper home".
[src:london/10-downing-street] Despite these exceptions, Number 10 has been known as the prime minister's official home for over one hundred years.
[src:london/10-downing-street] By the turn of the 20th century, photography and the penny press had linked Number 10 in the public mind with the premiership.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The introduction of films and television would strengthen this association.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Pictures of prime ministers with distinguished guests at the door became commonplace.
[src:london/10-downing-street] With or without the prime minister present, visitors had their picture taken.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Suffragettes posed in front of the door when they petitioned H.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Asquith for women's rights in 1913, a picture that became famous and was circulated around the world.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1931, Mahatma Gandhi, wearing a traditional homespun *dhoti*, posed leaving Number 10 after meeting with Ramsay MacDonald to discuss India's independence.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This picture, too, became famous, especially in India.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The freedom fighters could see their leader had been received in the prime minister's home.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Couse's elegant, understated door – stark black, framed in cream white with a bold white "10" clearly visible – was the perfect backdrop to record such events.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Prime Ministers made historic announcements from the front step.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Waving the Anglo-German Agreement of Friendship, Neville Chamberlain proclaimed "Peace with honour" in 1938 from Number 10 after his meeting with Adolf Hitler in Munich.
[src:london/10-downing-street] During World War II, Churchill was photographed many times emerging confidently from Number 10 holding up two fingers in the sign for "Victory".
[src:london/10-downing-street] The building itself, however, did not escape the London Blitz entirely unscathed; in February 1944 a bomb fell on nearby Horse Guards Parade and some of the drawing-room windows were destroyed.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The symbol of British government, Number 10 became a gathering place for protesters.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Emmeline Pankhurst and other suffragette leaders stormed Downing Street in 1908; anti-Vietnam War protestors marched there in the 1960s, as did anti-Iraq War protestors in 2005.
[src:london/10-downing-street] By the middle of the 20th century, Number 10 was falling apart again.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The deterioration had been obvious for some time.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The number of people allowed in the upper floors was limited for fear the bearing walls would collapse.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The staircase had sunk several inches; some steps were buckled and the balustrade was out of alignment.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The interior wood in the Cabinet Room's double columns was like sawdust.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Skirting boards, doors, sills and other woodwork were riddled and weakened with disease.
[src:london/10-downing-street] After reconstruction had begun, miners dug down into the foundations and found that the huge wooden beams supporting the house had decayed.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1958, a committee under the chairmanship of the Earl of Crawford and Balcarres was appointed by Harold Macmillan to investigate the condition of the house and make recommendations.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The interior would be photographed, measured, disassembled, and restored.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A new foundation with deep piles would be laid and the original buildings reassembled on top of it, allowing for much needed expansion and modernisation.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Any original materials that were beyond repair – such as the pair of double columns in the Cabinet Room – would be replicated in detail.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This was a formidable undertaking: the three buildings contained over 200 rooms spread out over five floors.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The architect Raymond Erith carried out the design for this painstaking work and the contractor that undertook it was John Mowlem & Co.
[src:london/10-downing-street] *The Times* reported initially that the cost for the project would be £400,000.
[src:london/10-downing-street] After more careful studies were completed, it was concluded that the "total cost was likely to be £1,250,000" and the work would take two years to complete.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In the end, the cost was close to £3,000,000 and the work took almost three years due in large part to 14 labour strikes.
[src:london/10-downing-street] There were also delays when archaeological excavations uncovered important artefacts dating from Roman, Saxon and medieval times.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Macmillan lived in Admiralty House during the reconstruction.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The new foundation was made of steel-reinforced concrete with pilings sunk 6 to 18 feet (1.8 to 5.5 m).
[src:london/10-downing-street] The "new" Number 10 consisted of about 60% new materials; the remaining 40% was either restored or replicas of originals.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Many rooms and sections of the new building were reconstructed exactly as they were in the old Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] These included: the garden floor, the door and entrance foyer, the stairway, the hallway to the Cabinet Room, the Cabinet Room, the garden and terrace, the Small and Large State Rooms and the three reception rooms.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The staircase, however, was rebuilt and simplified.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Steel was hidden inside the columns in the Pillared Drawing Room to support the floor above.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The upper floors were modernised and the third floor extended over Numbers 11 and 12 to allow more living space.
[src:london/10-downing-street] As many as 40 coats of paint were stripped from the elaborate cornices in the main rooms revealing details unseen for almost 200 years in some cases.
[src:london/10-downing-street] When builders examined the exterior façade, they discovered that the black colour visible even in photographs from the mid-19th century was misleading; the bricks were actually yellow.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The black appearance was the product of two centuries of pollution.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To preserve the 'traditional' look of recent times, the newly cleaned yellow bricks were painted black to resemble their well-known appearance.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Although the reconstruction was generally considered an architectural triumph, Erith was disappointed.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He complained openly during and after the project that the government had altered his design to save money.
[src:london/10-downing-street] "I am heart broken by the result," he said.
[src:london/10-downing-street] "The whole project has been a frightful waste of money because it just has not been done properly.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Ministry of Works has insisted on economy after economy.
[src:london/10-downing-street] I am bitterly disappointed with what has happened." Erith described the numbers on the front, intended to be based on historical models, as 'a mess' and 'completely wrong' to a fellow historian.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Within a few years, dry rot was discovered, especially in the main rooms due to inadequate waterproofing and a broken water pipe.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Extensive reconstruction again had to be undertaken in the late 1960s to resolve these problems.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Further extensive repairs and remodelling, commissioned by Margaret Thatcher, were completed in the 1980s under the direction of Erith's associate Quinlan Terry.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The work done by Erith and Terry in the 1960s and 1980s represents the most extensive remodelling of Number 10 in recent times.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Since 1990 when the Terry reconstruction was completed, repairing, redecorating, remodelling, and updating the house has been ongoing as needed.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The IRA mortar attack in February 1991 led to extensive work being done to repair the damage (mostly to the garden and exterior walls) and to improve security.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In the summer of 1993 windows were rebuilt and in 1995 computer cables installed.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1997, the building was remodelled to provide extra space for the prime minister's greatly increased staff.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To accommodate their large families, both Tony Blair and David Cameron chose to live in the private residence above Number 11 rather than the smaller one above Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 2010, the Camerons completely modernised the 50-year-old private kitchen in Number 11.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In March 2020, Boris Johnson refurbished the residential apartment at Number 11.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This became the subject of public controversy, and an Electoral Commission inquiry took place into the financing of the refurbishment.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In May 2023, a car was driven into the Downing Street gates.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Rishi Sunak was present inside the residences at the time.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A man was arrested by police and the car crash was not terrorism-related.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The current prime minister is Keir Starmer.
[src:london/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street houses the Cabinet Room, in which Cabinet meetings take place, chaired by the prime minister.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It also houses the Prime Minister's Executive Office, which deals with government logistics and diplomacy.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Number 10's door is the product of the renovations Charles Townshend ordered in 1766; it was probably not completed until 1772.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Executed in the Georgian style by the architect Kenton Couse, it is unassuming and narrow, consisting of a single white stone step leading to a modest brick front.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The small, six-panelled door, originally made of black oak, is surrounded by cream-coloured casing and adorned with a semicircular fanlight window.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Painted in white, between the top and middle sets of panels, is the number "10".
[src:london/10-downing-street] The zero of the number "10" is painted in a very eccentric style, in a 37° angle anticlockwise.
[src:london/10-downing-street] One theory is that this is in fact a capital 'O' as found in the Trajan alphabet that was used by the Ministry of Works at the time.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A black iron knocker in the shape of a lion's head is between the two middle panels; below the knocker is a brass letter box with the inscription "First Lord of the Treasury".
[src:london/10-downing-street] The doorbell is inscribed with "PUSH" although is rarely used in practice.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A black ironwork fence with spiked newel posts runs along the front of the house and up each side of the step to the door.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The fence rises above the step into a double-swirled archway, supporting an iron gas lamp surmounted by a crown.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In modern times the door cannot be opened from the outside; there is always someone inside to grant entry.
[src:london/10-downing-street] After the IRA mortar attack in 1991, the original black oak door was replaced by a blast-proof steel one.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Regularly removed for refurbishment and replaced with a replica, it is so heavy that it takes eight men to lift it.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The brass letterbox still bears the legend "First Lord of the Treasury".
[src:london/10-downing-street] The original door was put on display in the Churchill Museum at the Cabinet War Rooms.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Beyond the door, Couse installed black and white marble tiles in the entrance hall that are still in use.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A guard's chair designed by Thomas Chippendale sits in one corner.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Once used when policemen sat on watch outside in the street, it has an unusual "hood" designed to protect them from the wind and cold and a drawer underneath where hot coals were placed to provide warmth.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Scratches on the right arm were caused by their pistols rubbing up against the leather.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Couse also added a bow front to the small cottage – formerly Mr Chicken's house – incorporated into Number 10 in Walpole's time.
[src:london/10-downing-street] When William Kent rebuilt the interior between 1732 and 1734, his craftsmen created a stone triple staircase.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The main section had no visible supports.
[src:london/10-downing-street] With a wrought iron balustrade, embellished with a scroll design, and mahogany handrail, it rises from the garden floor to the third floor.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Kent's staircase is the first architectural feature visitors see as they enter Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Black and white engravings and photographs of all the past prime ministers decorate the wall.
[src:london/10-downing-street] They are rearranged slightly to make room for a photograph of each new prime minister.
[src:london/10-downing-street] There is one exception: Winston Churchill is represented in two photographs.
[src:london/10-downing-street] At the bottom of the staircase are group photographs of prime ministers with their Cabinet ministers and representatives to imperial conferences.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In Kent's design for the enlarged Number 10, the Cabinet Room was a simple rectangular space with enormous windows.
[src:london/10-downing-street] As part of the renovations begun in 1783, it was extended, giving the space its modern appearance.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Probably not completed until 1796, this alteration was achieved by removing the east wall and rebuilding it several feet inside the adjoining secretaries' room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] At the entrance, a screen of two pairs of Corinthian columns was erected (to carry the extra span of the ceiling) supporting a moulded entablature that wraps around the room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Robert Taylor, the architect who executed this concept, was knighted on its completion.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The resulting small space, framed by the pillars, serves as an anteroom to the larger area.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Hendrick Danckerts' painting "The Palace of Whitehall" usually hangs in the vestibule.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It also contains two large bookcases that house the prime minister's library; Cabinet members traditionally donate to the collection on leaving office – a tradition that began with Ramsay MacDonald in 1931.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Although Kent intended the First Lord to use this space as his study, it has rarely served that purpose; it has almost always been the Cabinet Room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Stanley Baldwin used the Cabinet Room as his office.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A few prime ministers, such as Tony Blair, occasionally worked at the Cabinet Room table.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Painted off-white with large floor to ceiling windows along one of the long walls, the room is light and airy.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Three brass chandeliers hang from the high ceiling.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Cabinet table, purchased during the Gladstone era, dominates the room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The modern boat-shaped top, introduced by Harold Macmillan in the late 1950s, is supported by huge original oak legs.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The table is surrounded by carved, solid mahogany chairs that also date from the Gladstone era.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The prime minister's chair, the only one with arms, is situated midway along one side in front of the marble fireplace, facing the windows; when not in use, it is positioned at an angle for easy access.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The only picture in the room is a copy of a portrait of Robert Walpole by Jean-Baptiste van Loo hanging over the fireplace.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Number 10 has three inter-linked state drawing rooms: the Pillared Drawing Room, the Terracotta Drawing Room and the White Drawing Room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The largest is the Pillared Room thought to have been created in 1796 by Taylor.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Measuring 37 feet (11 m) long by 28 feet (8.5 m) wide, it takes its name from the twin Ionic pilasters with straight pediments at one end.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Today, there is a portrait of Queen Elizabeth I over the fireplace; during the Thatcher, Major and Blair ministries, a portrait of William Pitt by Romney was hung there.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A Persian carpet covers almost the entire floor.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A copy of a 16th-century original now kept in the Victoria and Albert Museum, there is an inscription woven into it that reads: "I have no refuge in the world other than thy threshold.
[src:london/10-downing-street] My head has no protection other than this porchway.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The work of a slave of the holy place, Maqsud of Kashan in the year 926" (the Islamic year corresponding to 1520).
[src:london/10-downing-street] In the restoration conducted in the late 1980s, Quinlan Terry restored the fireplace.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Executed in the Kentian style, the small Ionic pilasters in the over-mantel are miniature duplicates of the large Ionic pillars in the room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Ionic motif is also found in the door surrounds and panelling.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Sparsely furnished with a few chairs and sofas around the walls, the Pillared Room is usually used to receive guests before they go into the State Dining Room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] However, it is sometimes used for other purposes that require a large open space.
[src:london/10-downing-street] International agreements have been signed in this room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Tony Blair entertained the England Rugby Union team in the Pillared Room after they won the World Cup in 2003.
[src:london/10-downing-street] John Logie Baird gave Ramsay MacDonald a demonstration of his invention, the television, in this room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] After the Apollo 11 lunar landing in July 1969, Harold Wilson hosted a reception in the room for the astronauts Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins, in addition to the Cambridge scientist Francis Thomas Bacon, inventor of the alkaline fuel cell used to generate power for space capsules.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Terracotta Room is the middle of the three drawing rooms.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It was used as the dining room when Robert Walpole was prime minister.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The name changes according to the colour it is painted.
[src:london/10-downing-street] When Margaret Thatcher came to power it was the Blue Room; she had it re-decorated and renamed the Green Room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In the renovation of the 1980s, Quinlan Terry introduced large Doric order columns to this room in the door surrounds and designed a very large Palladian overmantel for the fireplace with small double Doric columns on each side with the royal arms above.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Terry also added an ornate gilded ceiling to give the rooms a more stately look.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Carved into the plasterwork above the door leading to the Pillared Room is a tribute to Margaret Thatcher: a straw-carrying 'thatcher'.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The White State Drawing room was, until the 1940s, for the private use of prime ministers and their spouses.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It was here that Edward Heath kept his grand piano.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It is often used as the backdrop for television interviews and is in regular use as a meeting room for Downing Street staff.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The room links through to the Terracotta Room next door.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In the reconstruction during the late 1980s, Quinlan Terry used Corinthian columns and added ornate Baroque-style central ceiling mouldings and corner mouldings of the four national flowers of the United Kingdom: rose (England), thistle (Scotland), daffodil (Wales) and shamrock (Northern Ireland).
[src:london/10-downing-street] When Frederick Robinson (later Lord Goderich), became Chancellor of the Exchequer in 1823, he decided to leave a personal legacy to the nation.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To this end, he employed John Soane, the distinguished architect who had designed the Bank of England and many other famous buildings, to build a State Dining Room for Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Begun in 1825 and completed in 1826 at a cost of £2,000, the result is a spacious room with oak panelling and reeded mouldings.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Accessed through the first floor, its vaulted, arched ceiling rises up through the next so that it actually occupies two floors.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Measuring 42 by 26 feet (12.8 by 7.9 m), it is the largest room in Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Soane was the guest of honour when the dining room was first used on 4 April 1826.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The room is usually furnished with a table surrounded by 20 reproduction Adam style chairs originally made for the British Embassy in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:london/10-downing-street] For larger gatherings, a horseshoe-shaped table is brought in that will accommodate up to 65 guests.
[src:london/10-downing-street] On these occasions, the table is set with the Silver Trust Silver set given to Downing Street in the 1990s.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Above the fireplace, overlooking the room, is a massive portrait by John Shackleton of George II, the king who originally gave the building to the First Lord of the Treasury in 1732.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Celebrity chefs such as Nigella Lawson have cooked for Prime Ministers' guests using the small kitchen next door.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Entering through the Small Dining Room, Blair used this room for his monthly press conferences.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The great kitchen located in the basement was another part of the renovations begun in 1783, probably also under the direction of Robert Taylor.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Seldom seen by anyone other than staff, the space is two storeys high with a huge arched window and vaulted ceiling.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Traditionally, it has always had a chopping block work table in the centre that is 14 feet (4.3 m) long, 3 feet (0.91 m) wide and 5 inches (13 cm) thick.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Above Taylor's vaulted kitchen, between the Pillared Room and the State Dining room, Soane created a Smaller Dining Room (sometimes called the Breakfast Room) that still exists.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To build it, Soane removed the chimney from the kitchen to put a door in the room.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He then moved the chimney to the east side, running a Y-shaped split flue inside the walls up either side of one of the windows above.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The room therefore has a unique architectural feature: over the fireplace there is a window instead of the usual chimney breast.
[src:london/10-downing-street] With its flat unadorned ceiling, simple mouldings and deep window seats, the Small Dining Room is intimate and comfortable.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Usually furnished with a mahogany table seating only eight, Prime Ministers have often used this room when dining with family or when entertaining special guests on more personal state occasions.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The terrace and garden were constructed in 1736 shortly after Walpole moved into Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The terrace, extending across the back, provides a full view of St James's Park.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The garden is dominated by a 0.5 acres (0.20 ha) open lawn which wraps around Numbers 10 and 11 in an L-shape.
[src:london/10-downing-street] No longer "fitted with variety Walle fruit and diverse fruit trees" as it was in the 17th century, there is now a centrally located flower bed around a holly tree surrounded by seats.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Tubs of flowers line the steps from the terrace; around the walls are rose beds with flowering and evergreen shrubs.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The terrace and garden have provided a casual setting for many gatherings of First Lords with foreign dignitaries, Cabinet ministers, guests, and staff.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Prime Minister Tony Blair, for example, hosted a farewell reception in 2007 for his staff on the terrace.
[src:london/10-downing-street] John Major announced his 1995 resignation as leader of the Conservative Party in the garden.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Churchill called his secretaries the "garden girls" because their offices overlook the garden.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It was also the location of the first press conference announcing the Coalition Government between David Cameron's Conservatives and Nick Clegg's Liberal Democrats.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Number 10 is filled with fine paintings, sculptures, busts and furniture.
[src:london/10-downing-street] About half belong to the Government Art Collection.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The remainder are on loan from private collectors and from public galleries such as the National Portrait Gallery, the Tate Gallery, the Victoria and Albert Museum and the National Gallery.
[src:london/10-downing-street] About a dozen paintings are changed annually.
[src:london/10-downing-street] More extensive changes occur when a new prime minister takes office and redecorates.
[src:london/10-downing-street] These redecorations may reflect both individual taste as well as make a political statement.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Edward Heath borrowed French paintings from the National Gallery and was loaned two Renoirs from a private collector.
[src:london/10-downing-street] When Margaret Thatcher arrived in 1979 she insisted that the artwork had to be British and that it celebrate "British achievers".
[src:london/10-downing-street] As a former chemist, she took pleasure in devoting the Small Dining Room to a collection of portraits of British scientists, such as Joseph Priestley and Humphry Davy.
[src:london/10-downing-street] During the 1990s John Major converted the first floor anteroom into a small gallery of modern art, mostly British.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He also introduced several paintings by John Constable and J.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Turner, Britain's two best known 19th-century artists, and cricketing paintings by Archibald Stuart-Wortley including a portrait of one of England's most celebrated batsmen W.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In addition to outstanding artwork, Number 10 contains many exceptional pieces of furniture either owned by the house or on loan.
[src:london/10-downing-street] One of the most striking and unusual is the already mentioned Chippendale hooded guard's chair that sits in a corner of the entrance hall.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To its left is a long case clock by Benson of Whitehaven.
[src:london/10-downing-street] A similar clock by Samuel Whichcote of London stands in the Cabinet anteroom.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The White State Drawing Room contains examples of Adam furniture.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Green State Drawing Room contains mostly Chippendale furniture including a card table that belonged to Clive of India and a mahogany desk that is thought to have belonged to William Pitt the Younger and used by him during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In addition to the large carpet previously described, the Pillared State Drawing Room also contains a marble-topped table by Kent.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The State Dining Room contains a mahogany sideboard by Adam.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Until the late 19th century, Prime Ministers were required to furnish Number 10 at their own expense with furniture, tableware, china, linens, curtains and decorations.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This arrangement began to change in 1877 when Benjamin Disraeli took up residency.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He insisted that the Treasury should bear the cost of furnishings at least in the public areas.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The Treasury agreed and a complex accounting procedure was developed whereby the outgoing prime minister was required to pay for "wear and tear" on furnishings that had been purchased by the Treasury.
[src:london/10-downing-street] This system was used until November 1897 when the Treasury assumed responsibility for purchasing and maintaining almost all of the furnishings in both the public and private areas except decorating the walls with art work.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In 1924 when Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald took office, he did not own nor have the means to buy an extensive art collection.
[src:london/10-downing-street] He had the Government Art Collection loan pieces.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The arrangement became the standard practice.
[src:london/10-downing-street] To celebrate, Thatcher hosted a grand dinner in the State Dining Room for her living predecessors: Harold Macmillan, Alec Douglas-Home, Harold Wilson, Edward Heath and James Callaghan.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Also in attendance were Elizabeth II and representatives of the families of every 20th-century Prime Minister since H.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Asquith, including Lady Olwen Carey Evans (daughter of David Lloyd George), Lady Leonora Howard (daughter of Stanley Baldwin), and Clarissa Avon (widow of Anthony Eden and niece of Winston Churchill).
[src:london/10-downing-street] That same year, the Leisure Circle published Christopher Jones' book *No.
[src:london/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street, The Story of a House*.
[src:london/10-downing-street] In the foreword, Thatcher described her feelings for Number 10: "How much I wish that the public ... could share with me the feeling of Britain's historic greatness which pervades every nook and cranny of this complicated and meandering old building ...
[src:london/10-downing-street] All Prime Ministers are intensely aware that, as tenants and stewards of No.
[src:london/10-downing-street] 10 Downing Street, they have in their charge one of the most precious jewels in the nation's heritage".
[src:london/10-downing-street] For most of its history, Number 10 was accessible to the public.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Early security consisted of two police officers: one stood guard outside the door; the other was stationed inside to open it.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Since the door had no keyhole, the inside officer depended upon the lone outside officer.
[src:london/10-downing-street] During Thatcher's premiership, terrorist threats led to the implementation of a second level of security.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Despite the added measure, on 7 February 1991, the Provisional IRA used a van they parked in Whitehall to launch a mortar bomb at Number 10.
[src:london/10-downing-street] It exploded in the back garden, while Prime Minister John Major was holding a Cabinet meeting.
[src:london/10-downing-street] Major moved to Admiralty House while repairs were being completed.
[src:london/10-downing-street] The attack led to the famous black door being replaced with a new blast-proof door and the addition of guardhouses at the street ends as well as other less visible measures to further improve security of Downing Street.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The building adjoins the Lloyd's Building, also designed by Richard Rogers.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The previous, 1960s building on the site was owned by British Land and had been designed by Gollins Melvin Ward.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] By December 2009, the site was cleared but construction stalled because of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The project was revived in 2010 by Oxford Properties in partnership with British Land.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] From 1840, P&O had occupied the offices of Willcox & Anderson.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] However, business east of the Gulf of Suez increased in the late 1840s, so it needed larger offices.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In 1845, the company purchased the King's Arms inn and hotel at 122 Leadenhall Street for £7,250.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] A new office building on the site cost it about £8,000 and opened in 1848.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In 1854, the company expanded its offices with a lease on 121 Leadenhall Street, and further 80 year leases from St Thomas's Hospital on dwellings at 123, 124 and 125 which were demolished to create a new frontage for 122.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] By the mid-1960s, the company sought more office space from its narrow site.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Commercial Union Assurance Company planned a redevelopment on the adjacent site at the corner of St Mary Axe but that had poor access.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] To achieve a satisfactory planning consent and optimise floor space the two companies carried out a joint development, with adjustment of boundaries, and creation of an open concourse at the junction of Leadenhall Street and St Mary Axe.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Gollins Melvin Ward's 1969 building at 122 Leadenhall Street was 54 m (177 ft) tall with 14 storeys above grade and three below.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] It matched Commercial Union's new, adjacent headquarters, later St Helen's.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The building had a central, compressional concrete core and suspended floors hung using steel 'chords', visible on the exterior, themselves hung from power trusses at the top of the building.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The architect acknowledged the influence of Mies van der Rohe.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The building was extensively damaged by an IRA bomb in the early-1990s and subsequently had to be reclad.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Tenants included the Italian International Bank and Calyon.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In 2007–08, McGee contracted to demolish the building for £16 million.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] After stripping the interior and removal of low level structures, the suspended parts of the building had to be dismantled floor by floor from the bottom.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Designed by Richard Rogers and developed by British Land and Oxford Properties, the new Leadenhall Building is 225 m (737 ft) tall, with 48 floors.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The planning application was submitted to the City of London Corporation in February 2004 and was approved in May 2005.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In 2006 Scheme Design (RIBA Stage D) started.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In a statement made to the London Stock Exchange on 14 August 2008, British Land said it was delaying the project, which was due to start in October 2010.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] On 22 December 2010, the developer announced the project was moving forward with contracts being signed for the 50/50 joint venture with Oxford Properties.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The new tower features a tapered glass façade on one side which reveals steel bracings, along with a ladder frame to emphasise the vertical appearance of the building.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] It also appears to anchor the tower to the ground, giving a sense of strength.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Unlike other tall buildings, which typically use a concrete core to provide stability, the steel "Megaframe", engineered by Arup, provides stability to the entire structure and is the world's tallest of its kind.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The base features a 30m high atrium which is open to the public and extends the adjacent plaza.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The flat side of the building is also encased in glass, and houses the mechanical services – in particular the elevator shafts.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] These have been turned into an architectural feature, similar to the neighbouring Lloyd's Building – they deliberately display the elevator machinery, with bright orange counterweights and elevator motors.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] This unusual design's main drawback is the building's relatively small floorspace (84,424 m2) for a building of its height.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] It is hoped that the slanting wedge-shaped design will have less impact on the protected sightline of St Paul's Cathedral when viewed from Fleet Street and the west.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In July 2011, British Land and Oxford Properties announced that Laing O'Rourke was the main contractor for the works of the new Leadenhall Building.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Throughout 2011, construction began with the basement floors.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] By December 2012, the steelwork had progressed up to the fifth mega-level, with topping out expected in February or March.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The glass cladding had also begun to rise.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In May 2013, the co-developers announced that the building was over 51% pre-let.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] By June 2013, the steelwork of the building was completely topped out with the glass cladding covering almost half the building.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The construction of the building was the subject of an episode of the *Super Skyscrapers* documentary series by the American television channel PBS in February 2014.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In November 2014, two embrittled bolts broke and fell from the building.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Severfield, who had supplied and erected the building's structural steel, announced a £6 million charge for remediation works that were settled in 2019.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Severfield had already booked £9.9 million of losses on the project in 2012.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Leeds-based Andrews Fasteners Ltd, which went into administration, supplied the 3,000 defective 'megabolts', each the size of a human arm.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Severfield had not used the bolts before and its chief executive said it would be unlikely to do so in the future.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] During the 2017 redevelopment of nearby 22 Bishopsgate, a suspended girder struck the 122 Leadenhall Street building.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Severfield was also the steel frame subcontractor to Multiplex's Bishopsgate site.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] The development has succeeded in attracting tenants, especially in contrast to the nearby part-built Pinnacle and completed Heron Tower.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] In May 2011, it was announced that the lower 10 floors of the Leadenhall Building have been pre-let to insurance broker Aon, which moved its global headquarters to London from Chicago.
[src:london/122-leadenhall-street] Insurance group Amlin has also agreed terms on a 20-year lease of the 19th to 24th floors as well as the top floor, the 45th, from March 2015, for a total of 111,000 sq ft of office space.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On 15 February 2003, a coordinated day of protests was held across the world in which people in more than 600 cities expressed opposition to the imminent Iraq War.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was part of a series of protests and political events that had begun in 2002 and continued as the invasion, war, and occupation took place.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The day was described by social movement researchers as "the largest protest event in human history".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to BBC News, between six and ten million people took part in protests in up to sixty countries over the weekend of 15 and 16 February.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in Europe.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The one in Rome involved around three million people, and is listed in the 2004 *Guinness Book of World Records* as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Madrid hosted the second largest rally with more than 1.5 million people protesting against the invasion of Iraq.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, three smaller protests were held the following day, attended by foreigners and domestic students.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2002, the United States government began to argue for the necessity of invading Iraq.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This formally began with a speech by US President George W.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bush to the United Nations General Assembly on 12 September 2002 which argued that the Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein was violating United Nations (UN) resolutions, primarily on weapons of mass destruction, and that this necessitated action.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposed war was controversial with many people questioning the motives of the US government and its rationale.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One poll which covered 41 countries claimed that less than 10% would support an invasion of Iraq without UN sanction and that half would not support an invasion under any circumstances.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war groups worldwide organised public protests.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the French academic Dominique Reynié, between 3 January and 12 April 2003, 36 million people across the globe took part in almost 3,000 anti‑war protests, the demonstrations on 15 February 2003 being the largest and most prolific.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The 15 February international protests were unprecedented not only in terms of the size of the demonstrations but also in terms of the international coordination involved.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Immanuel Wallerstein has spoken of the international protests as being organised by the forces of "the camps of Porto Alegre and Davos" in reference to the emergence of global social movements who had been organising around international events such as the 2001 World Social Forum in Porto Alegre.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The idea for an international day of demonstrations was first raised by the British anti-capitalist group Globalise Resistance (GR) in the wake of an anti-war demonstration in Britain of 400,000 on 28 September.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time GR was involved in planning for the Florence European Social Forum (ESF) and brought up the suggestion at an ESF planning meeting.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to GR's Chris Nineham, "There was considerable controversy.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Some delegates were worried it would alienate the mainstream of the movement.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposal was accepted and at the final rally of the ESF, in November 2002, the call officially went out for Europe-wide demonstrations on 15 February 2003.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This call was firmed up in December at a planning meeting for the following ESF which took place in Copenhagen in 2003.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This meeting was attended by delegates from many European anti-war organisations, the US group United for Peace and Justice, and representatives of groups from the Philippines.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The decision was taken to set up a Europe-wide anti-war website and to commit to spreading organisational coordination both within and beyond Europe.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An email network connecting the different national organisations across Europe, and eventually also the different US groups, was set up.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In December 2002, the Cairo Anti-war Conference pledged to organize demonstrations in Egypt and the International Campaign Against Aggression on Iraq (which came out of the Cairo conference) sought to co-ordinate more demonstrations across the world.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around this time, the US anti-war group International ANSWER called for actions in North America supporting the proposed protests in Europe.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another important platform for the spreading call to demonstrate internationally occurred at the World Social Forum in Porto Alegre, Brazil which took place at the end of 2002.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] European delegates sought to popularize the plan for the increasingly international demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They met with some success, including the organisation of an anti‑war assembly which was attended by almost 1,000 people.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The song "Boom!", by System of a Down, had a music video filmed on the day of the protest, showing the many protest locations and people's opinions on the Iraq War.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations took place across Europe and some of the largest drawing attendance figures in the tens of thousands in many cities.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately one-fifth of the total demonstrators worldwide protested in Europe.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austria, 30,000 people (SW estimate) took to the streets of its capital, Vienna.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Switzerland in order to "concentrate the movement" most activists agreed to organise a single demonstration for the whole country in Bern.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day roughly 40,000 people joined the protest in front of the Bundeshaus, the seat of the Swiss federal government and parliament.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration, which ran under the slogan **Nein zum Krieg gegen Irak – Kein Blut für Öl!** (No to war in Iraq – no blood for oil!) was the largest in Switzerland since 1945.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Slovenia, roughly 3,000 people gathered in Ljubljana's central park of Congress Square, supported by the mayor Danica Simšič, and marched the streets in one of the largest demonstrations since independence in 1991.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Benelux countries had large demonstrations for their total population size.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Belgium organisers had expected around 30,000 people to attend a demonstration in Brussels, which is the home of the European Parliament.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They were shocked by a turn out of approximately 100,000 people (WSWS and GLW estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march took over 3 hours to cross the city.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Netherlands saw around 70,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 75,000 people (WSWS estimate) protest in Amsterdam.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was the country's largest demonstration since the anti-nuclear campaigns of the 1980s.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti war website antiwar.com reports that 8,000-14,000 people were present at protests in Luxembourg, however they do not provide a citation for this figure.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bosnia and Herzegovina saw around 100 protesters gather in Mostar.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This protest spanned the sectarian divide with both Bosniaks and Croats attending.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in Croatia where 10,000 people (WSWS estimate) took part in a protest in the capital city of Zagreb.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Croatia also saw protests in Osijek, Vukovar, Knin, Zadar, Šibenik, Split and Dubrovnik.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Cyprus saw a demonstration of between 500 (*USA Today* estimate) and more than 800 people (SW estimate) at the British army base in Dhekelia.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Enduring heavy rain protesters briefly blocked the base.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They then marched to Pyla village where they watched other demonstrations occurring across the world on a giant screen.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was mostly attended by Greek Cypriots but they were joined by some Turkish Cypriots.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the Czech Republic, over 1,000 people joined a rally at Jan Palach Square in Prague.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Czech philosopher Erazim Kohak addressed the crowd, saying, "War is not a solution, war is a problem." Protesters listened to music and speeches before marching to the Czech government building, where they submitted petitions, then march continued to the US embassy.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In France, there were demonstrations in somewhere between twenty (*Observer* estimate) and eighty cities (WSWS estimate); the organisers estimated that over half a million marched in total.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration took place in Paris, where around 100,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 200,000 (WSWS estimate) people marched through the streets, ending in a rally at the Place de la Bastille.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This location's role in the French Revolution was considered to give it a historical significance.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Toulouse of around 10,000 people.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Germany, coaches brought people from over 300 German towns to Berlin to join a demonstration of 300,000 (police estimate) to 500,000 (organizers' estimate) people; the largest demonstration that had occurred in Berlin for several decades.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters, including members of Gerhard Schröder's government, filled the boulevard between the Brandenburg Gate and the Victory Column.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Athens, Greece, 150,000 people (WSWS estimate) demonstrated.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was generally peaceful, but a small group clashed with police.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police fired tear gas at the group some of whom threw rocks and petrol bombs.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police reported that the trouble was down to a group of anarchists who had split off from the main demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Ireland, the Dublin march was only expected to draw 20,000 people, but the actual figure was given variously as 80,000 (police estimate), 90,000 (BBC estimate), 100,000 (*Guardian* estimate) or 150,000 (Socialist Worker (SW) estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march went from Parnell Square, passing the Department of Foreign Affairs at St.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Stephen's Green, and on to the Dame Street for a rally where popular Irish folk singer Christy Moore, Kíla and Labour Party politician Michael D.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Higgins were among many speakers from the platform.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march disrupted traffic for more than four hours.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters demanded that the Irish government stop allowing the United States military to use Ireland's Shannon Airport as a transatlantic stop-off point in bringing soldiers to the Middle East.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the global day of protest took place in Italy in Rome.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Nearly 3,000 buses and thirty trains were specially chartered to bring people to the demonstration, which was organised under the slogan "Stop the war; no ifs or buts".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The organisers were shocked at the size of the turn out and the unexpected number of people forced the demonstration to set off two hours early.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The size of the demonstration meant that the majority of demonstrators did not make it into the final rally and in total three million people (organisers' estimate, supported by the Guinness Book of World Records) were on the streets.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was listed in the 2004 Guinness Book of World Records as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the *Green Left Weekly* (GLW), the demonstration contained people from across Italian society; "Catholic nuns and priests marched alongside young people with dreadlocks, nose rings and Palestinian scarves.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Christians, anarchists and communists mingled".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately 1,000 demonstrated (SW estimate) in Malta.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] After the demonstration an anti-war concert was held in the capital, Valletta.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Norway saw its biggest series of protests since 1917.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in its capital Oslo were more than 60,000 protesters (Police estimate and Socialist Worker estimate) joining a demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of around 15,000 took place in Bergen and Trondheim, and 10,000 in Stavanger.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests also took place in at least 30 towns across the country.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the rally in Oslo the vice-chair of the Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions (LO) spoke from the platform claiming that "Bush only cares about American oil interests".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Denmark 20,000 to 30,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) took part in a march in the capital city, Copenhagen.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Sweden, 35,000 demonstrated in Stockholm. and about 25,000 in Gothenburg.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Helsinki, Finland, an estimated 15,000 people participated in one of the largest mass-protests in the republic's history.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was a demonstration in Warsaw, Poland of 10,000 people (SW estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration through central Warsaw passed the US embassy.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another protest, organized by the local Wrocław Anti-War Coalition (WKA), was held in the city of Wrocław in the market square by the town hall, with 400–500 people participating.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lisbon, police estimated that around 35,000 people gathered to march through the city.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Three former Portuguese prime ministers were in attendance.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Russia, which had several demonstrations, the largest occurred in Moscow, with 200,000 people (WSWS estimate) in attendance.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small demonstrations also took place in Serbia, where there was a demonstration of 200 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Belgrade.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was estimated that 1,000 people marched in the capital of Slovakia, Bratislava.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Barcelona also had a large, with estimates of 350,000 (Delegación de Gobierno), 1,300,000 (Barcelona city hall and Police) or 1,500,000 (GLW) people joining a demonstration which moved from the Passeig de Gràcia to the Plaça de Tetuan.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The city of Oviedo had a population of 180,000 and a turnout of 100,000.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The main demonstration in Turkey took place in Istanbul, thousands (SW estimate) demonstrated.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The local authorities had banned the protest claiming to have worries about national security, however the protest organisers went ahead with the rally under the cover of calling a press conference.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations in Adana, Ankara, İzmir, Zonguldak, İzmit, Antalya and Muğla.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Ukraine of around 2,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a "Rock against the war" rally in Kyiv's central square.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the lead-up to 15 February, the Stop the War Coalition was organising the march from a small office donated by the National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They planned for the two marches to merge at Piccadilly Circus and then proceed to a rally at Hyde Park.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The negotiations for this plan faltered when the Labour government's Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport Tessa Jowell initially instructed the Royal Parks agency to deny permission for the rally in Hyde Park for safety reasons and to protect the grass.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Trafalgar Square was suggested by Jowell as the alternative venue, but the Mayor of London Ken Livingstone insisted it was of insufficient size.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The government's decision was reversed by 5 February.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sections of the media supported this demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The *Daily Mirror* gave large coverage in the lead up to the march and provided thousands of placards on the day.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration also received sponsorship support from Greenpeace and Mecca-Cola.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As the date for the march approached the BBC was predicting that around 500,000 people would attend, while StWC was hoping for numbers to top the symbolically significant million mark.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The British Stop the War Coalition (Stop) claimed the protest in London was the largest political demonstration in the city's history.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police estimated attendance as well in excess of 750,000 people and the BBC estimated that around a million attended.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The weather, on the day of the protest was grey and cold, but reports noted that people remained "in high spirits" as London became gridlocked and protesters were stuck for hours at Gower Street and the Embankment, the two starting points for the march.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police began the march earlier than intended on safety grounds because of the number of people who had arrived in central London.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Hundreds of coaches brought protesters from 250 towns and cities across the UK, with around 100 coaches coming from Wales alone.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many commentators noted the diversity of those attending the march.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] All police leave in the capital was cancelled for the event, though Scotland Yard later said that it passed off almost without incident.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters who managed to reach Hyde Park in time heard various speakers, including Harold Pinter, George Galloway, Tony Benn and Bianca Jagger however many were not able to reach the rally as those travelling home by coach had to leave before completing the march route.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters at the back end of the march did not reach Hyde Park until hours after the speakers and performers had finished.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Charles Kennedy, then the leader of the Liberal Democrats, was a late addition to the list of speakers.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some media speculation that he only decided to speak after a lead article in *The Guardian* was critical of his absence from the planned speaker list.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Because of the size of the march, accurate estimates of the number of people in attendance are difficult.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It is relatively uncontentious that the march was the largest ever political demonstration in the UK and the biggest taking to the streets since the Golden Jubilee weekend in 2002.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In an ICM poll for *The Guardian* (14 February 2003 – 16 February 2003), 6% of people claimed that someone from their household went on the march or had intended to.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Stop claims that this translates into 1.25 million households and thus supports the estimate of two million people, assuming that more than one person could come from each household.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] RadioVague in conjunction with the now defunct CableRadio broadcast speeches, music and interviews from the event to the internet throughout the day using a satellite uplink provided by Psand.net.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A sole person demonstrated in opposition to the march outside the Iraqi section of the Jordanian Embassy on the day – Jacques More a writer from Croydon – with a placard saying that, although a last resort, war is necessary "[w]hen evil dictators rule and murder their own people".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Ten years on writer Ian Sinclair assembled an oral history of the demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Journalist Ellie Mae O'Hagan, a UK Uncut activist, told Sinclair that despite its size "it did absolutely nothing".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other witnesses, such as Milan Rai, are of the opposite opinion: "We achieved a lot, and a hell of a lot more than we realise".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tariq Ali, one of the speakers in February 2003, said at the tenth anniversary: "I didn't quite tell them 'Blair is going to go to war regardless of today' but I knew that".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "It was a huge show of anger but that's about it.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "One demonstration never overturned government policy overnight – or very rarely – and on something as strategic and massive as that", commented Seumas Milne in an interview with *The Quietus* online magazine in October 2012.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In addition to the demonstrations in England, the United Kingdom also saw protests in Scotland.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war activists planned a demonstration in Glasgow which ended at the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre (SECC) where the Labour Party was holding a conference for party members.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party requested that the SECC refuse permission for a stage and PA system outside the conference hall.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In response to this the then Scottish Socialist Party MSP Tommy Sheridan tabled a motion in the Scottish Parliament to allow the event to take place, condemning what he claimed were attempts to "stifle all opposition to warmonger Blair".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party was unsuccessful in blocking the demonstrators' plans.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tony Blair was due to give a speech at the same time as the protesters would have arrived outside the conference centre, but the speech was rescheduled to an earlier time to avoid this.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day around 50,000 people according to the *Guardian* joined the march, which started at Glasgow Green.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the time the front of the march had travelled the 2 miles (3.2 km) to the SECC, Blair had delivered his speech and had left the area.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Northern Irish march was held in Belfast, where 10,000 (*Guardian* estimate) to 20,000 (SW estimate) protesters from across the sectarian divide joined the demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march started at the Arts College at 14:30 and moved through that Royal Avenue towards Belfast City Hall.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Prominent politicians from Sinn Féin, the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) and the centrist Alliance Party joined the protest.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sinn Féin president Gerry Adams spoke from the platform at the end rally saying "If President Bush and Mr Blair want war, it should be war against poverty and for equality." There was also a rally in Newry in County Down attending by hundreds of protesters (BBC estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Canada saw protests in 70 cities and towns (WSWS estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in Montreal where more than 100,000 people protested (SW and WSWS each estimated 150,000) despite windchill temperatures below −30 °C (−22 °F).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 80,000 people joined a demonstration in Toronto, 40,000 in Vancouver, 18,000 (by police estimates) in Edmonton, 8,000 in Victoria, 4,000 in Halifax and 6,000 in Ottawa.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were protests in 70 cities in total.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] These demonstrations took place despite very cold weather, average temperatures were below −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Chicoutimi, 1,500 protested in windchill temperatures of −40 °C (−40 °F) wind-chill temperature in what was one of the coldest marches on that global day of protest.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place all across the United States of America with CBS reporting that 150 U.S. cities had protests.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the World Socialist Web Site, protests took place in 225 different communities.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in the nation's largest cities including Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York City, but there were also smaller rallies in towns such as Gainesville, Georgia; Macomb, Illinois; and Juneau, Alaska, among scores of others.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Organisers of the New York City protest had hoped to march past the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a week before the march, police claimed that they would not be able to ensure order and District Court Judge Barbara Jones ruled against allowing the route.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Instead, protesters were only permitted to hold a stationary rally.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On that day, over 300 buses and four special trains brought protesters in from across the country.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] BBC estimates that 100,000 protesters took part in a rally near the UN headquarters.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among those taking part was the 9/11 Families For Peaceful Tomorrows, a group made up of some relatives of victims of the attacks on the World Trade Center.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Speakers included politicians, church leaders and entertainers, such as actress Susan Sarandon and South African Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As people tried to reach the rally area they ended up constituting an unplanned march, stretching twenty blocks down First Avenue and overflowing onto Second and Third Avenue.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In total estimates range from 300,000 to 400,000 protesters (WSWS estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests were largely peaceful though a small group of protesters who were reported to have broken off from the main rally, caused damage to property in Union Square, and threw stones at police officers, which resulted in forty arrests.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were numerous complaints that the New York City Police Department (NYPD) were too heavy-handed.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many streets were blocked off and protesters reported feeling hemmed in and scared.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the end of the day, police reported that there had been roughly 275 arrests; organisers dispute this number, claiming that there were 348 arrests.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, NYPD spokesman Michael O'Looney denied the charges claiming that the tape was "filled with special effects" and that it did not prove the police had not been provoked.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At a demonstration in Los Angeles, California, 50,000 (WSWS estimate) to 60,000 (GLW estimate) protesters (CNN said "thousands") marched down Hollywood Boulevard filling it for four blocks.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Amongst the protesters were the actors Martin Sheen and Mike Farrell and director Rob Reiner.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Martin Sheen, who at the time was playing a fictitious U.S. president in *The West Wing*, said that "None of us can stop this war ... there is only one guy that can do that and he lives in the White House".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other activists in California originally planned to hold a protest in San Francisco on the Saturday but they changed to the Sunday in order not to conflict with the city's Chinese New Year's parade.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was held on Sunday 16 February.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The BBC estimated the crowd size to be 150,000 people, while protest organisers and police agreed that the crowd count was 200,000 people.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a *San Francisco Chronicle* photographic investigation estimated that the number in attendance at the peak period was closer to 65,000 people, although it did not state how many people were in attendance for the duration of the demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some controversy over Rabbi Michael Lerner not being selected as a speaker for the rally at the end of the demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Lerner claimed that he was not picked to speak for reasons of antisemitism due to his support for the existence of the Israeli state.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austin, Texas, 10,000 protestors marched down Congress Avenue from the state capitol building.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Colorado Springs, 4,000 protesters were dispersed with pepper spray, tear gas, stun guns and batons.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 34 were arrested on failure to disperse and other charges and at least two protesters had to have hospital treatment.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Seattle, organisers aimed to have 20 to 30 thousand people join a march from Seattle Center following a giant blue planet, the emblem adopted by the march organisers.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day 50,000 people (GLW estimate) turned out to protest under the dual slogan "Stop the war on Iraq; Stop the war on immigrants", more than on the Seattle protests against the WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations also took place in Philadelphia, where thousands (CNN estimate) joined a march to the Liberty Bell, and in Chicago, where 10,000 people demonstrated (GLW estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Florida a small number of protesters staged a naked protest on Palm Beach.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They initially had some problems getting permission for the action, but on the Thursday before, a U.S.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] District court ruled that the planned nude protest was legal at the public beach.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Most of the attendees had come from the four-day Mid-Winter Naturist Festival that was taking place at the same time.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration of 900 people (*USA Today* estimate) on the island of Puerto Rico.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The chief demonstration in Mexico took place in Mexico City where around 10,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a demonstration which ended with a rally at a heavily guarded US embassy.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among the demonstrators was Nobel Peace Prize laureate Rigoberta Menchú.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place across South America including Uruguay, where their protest took place on 14 February.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An estimated 70,000 people marched down Montevideo's Avenida 18.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Brazil, a protest led by President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva was attended by 1,500 marchers (Police estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Buenos Aires, Argentina, an estimate of 50,000 protesters attended which included some veterans of the Falklands War of 1982.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Areas in Asia with large Muslim populations, in particular the countries of the West Asia, had the highest levels of opposition to the proposed Iraq war, however demonstrations in many of these countries were relatively small.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The reasons for this are complex, but one factor that is commonly cited is the suppression of protest movements by the conservative leaders of those countries.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Iraq, the country in which the war would take place, protesters marched down Palestine Street in Baghdad where several thousand Iraqis—many carrying Kalashnikov rifles—joined in the global protests.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Unlike the vast majority of protests across the world the protest in Baghdad was also in support of the Baathist regime; it was called by Saddam Hussein as "World Anger Day".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters carried posters of Saddam and burned US flags.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A large protest also took place on the streets of Damascus in Syria, which borders Iraq.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters chanted anti-U.S. and anti-Israeli slogans while marching to the "People's Assembly" in a demonstration of between 10,000 (GLW estimate) to 200,000 protesters (CBS estimate and *USA Today* estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lebanon, 10,000 protesters (CBS, GLW estimate) took part in a demonstration in Beirut.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protest ended early when it rained heavily.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations of 5,000 people (GLW estimate) in Amman, Jordan.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Israel there was a demonstration in Tel Aviv of approximately 2,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 3,000 people (GLW and WSWS estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration contained both Arabs and Jews.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was organized by a wide range of organizations including the Communist Party of Israel, the National Democratic Assembly, the Arab Democratic Party, the Independent Media Center, the Alternative Information Center, Ta'ayush, the Gush Shalom movement, and the Organization for Democratic Action.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, it was boycotted by other left-wing groups, including Peace Now and Meretz.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was coordinated with a similar demonstration which took place in Ramallah.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests took place across Japan mostly being held outside US military bases.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the day took place in Shibuya, where 5,000 (SW estimate) people marched.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, there was a demonstration of 25,000 in Tokyo on Friday, the day before as well as smaller demonstrations in Osaka and other cities.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Tokyo protests contained Japanese veterans of World War II and survivors of the 1945 atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 3,000 people (SW estimate) joined an illegal demonstration in the Malaysian city of Kuala Lumpur despite police warnings that any participants in a protest would face stern action.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration ended at the US embassy at Jalan Tun Razak.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Taiwan had a protest of more than 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Taipei under the slogan of "No Blood for Oil".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] India saw protests across the country including 10,000 (BBC estimate) in Calcutta.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Bangladesh 2,000 people joined a demonstration in Dhaka.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In South Korea, there was a demonstration of 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) which took place in the capital city Seoul.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest started with a rally at Marronnier Park after which there was a demonstration that ended in Jongmyo were the size of the protest increased in size to 3,000 people (WSWS estimate).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Jongmyo was surrounded by riot police who almost out numbered the protesters.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests also took place in the South Korean cities of Busan, Daegu, Daejeon, Gwangju and Wonju.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, China, three protests were held the following day, attended by about 450 people in total, including foreigners and domestic students.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Johannesburg, around 8,000-10,000 people joined in a colorful and peaceful protest.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They toyi-toyied and marched, stopping at the U.S.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Consulate General where riot police formed a protective chain around the entrance.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Cape Town 5,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 20,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) joined a demonstration march which started at 10 in the morning on Keizersgracht road and ended at the offices of the US consulate-general which was guarded by a ring of riot police, where there was a rally with speakers.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests were organised by the Anti-War Coalition and the Stop the War campaign of the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu).
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of thousands of people also took place at Durban and Bloemfontein.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A number of prominent ANC politicians attended marches.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the Cape Town rally the South African Minister, Pallo Jordan addressed the protesters saying; "We will stop the war.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A protest of around 3,000 (SW estimate) in the Tunisian city of Sfax was attacked by police who beat the protesters with batons and truncheons, injuring at least 20.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests in Fiji took place on the day before, on Friday morning, heralding the weekend of demonstrations.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters handed floral Valentine's Day messages to the representatives of the US, British and Australian governments urging them to avoid the war.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Friday also saw protests in Melbourne, where around 150,000 people (BBC estimate) joined a demonstration.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the Saturday protests also took place in Australia's national capital (Canberra), with 20,000 protesters.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Sydney demonstration on Sunday 16 February included a feeder march of 10,000 trade unionists, with 200,000 (BBC estimate) to 250,000 (Sydney Morning Herald estimate) demonstrating in Sydney.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Across the six state capitals an estimated 600,000 demonstrated in cities around the country.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Beyond the capitals, many major cities and towns around Australia had protests.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At protests in Australia in Bellingen, New South Wales around 2,500 people (SW estimate) joined a rally at the towns sports ground.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As well as hearing from speakers, the demonstrators were entertained by a group of a cappella singers called 'The Bushbombs'.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The rally was about as large as the town's population.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The first actual demonstration of the day took place in New Zealand where 10,000 people demonstrated in Auckland and Wellington.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Auckland march was bigger than expected, forcing police to shut off Queen Street.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] People were reported to be still starting the march as those at the front of the march reached a rally in Myers Park several kilometres away.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Wellington the march had to carry on after the then planned end point as there were too many people to fit into the park.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 400 to 500 people marched in Hamilton.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in at least 18 other centres, including Dunedin, Thames, Opotiki, Whakatane, Whangarei, Timaru and Rotorua, and Picnic for Peace in Christchurch.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A group of scientists at the US McMurdo Station held a rally on the ice at the edge of the Ross Sea.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time, many commentators were hopeful that this global mobilization of unprecedented scale would stop the coming Iraq war.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] *The New York Times* writer Patrick Tyler claimed that they showed that there were "two superpowers on the planet – the United States, and worldwide public opinion".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The unprecedented size of the demonstrations was widely taken to indicate that the majority of people across the world opposed the war.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the potential effect of the protests was generally dismissed by pro-war politicians.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Her view was borne out as the day of protests, along with the protests that followed it, failed to stop the war.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protests and other public opposition were seen as a key factor in the decisions of the governments of many countries, such as Canada, to not send troops to Iraq, and of Turkey to deny coalition use of airbases in its territory.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests have also been cited as a factor strengthening the hand of the "uncommitted six" members of the United Nations Security Council - Angola, Cameroon, Chile, Mexico, and Pakistan.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Though demonstrations against the Iraq war and subsequent occupation continued, none of the demonstrations through to 2011 matched the 15 February protest in terms of size.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One suggested explanation for this is that people became disillusioned with marching as a political tactic because of the failure of these demonstrations to achieve their explicit aim.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2006, three years after the protest day, in an article arguing for people to attend a further march, Mike Marqusee put forward two counter arguments to this.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Firstly, he claimed that it was too soon to judge the long-term significance of the demonstrations.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As examples, he stated, "People who took part in the non-cooperation campaigns in India in the 20s and 30s had to wait a long time for independence," and "There were eight years of protest and more than 2 million dead before the Vietnam war came to an end".
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Secondly, he claimed that while the effect of marching may be uncertain, the effect of not marching would make it more likely that the occupation would continue.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Despite failing in its explicit aim, the 15 February global day of anti-war protests had many effects that, according to some, were not directly intended.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to United Kingdom left-wing anti-war activist Salma Yaqoob, one of these was that they were a powerful antidote to the idea that the war was a "Clash of Civilizations", or a religious war, an idea she claimed was propagated both by Western leaders and reactionary forces in the Arab world.
[src:london/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This is echoed in the words of former Hizb ut-Tahrir organiser Hadiya Masieh who said of the non-Muslims marching in London "How could we demonise people who obviously opposed aggression against Muslims?".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A severe outbreak of cholera occurred in 1854 near Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) and Golden Square in Soho, London, England, during the worldwide 1846–1860 cholera pandemic.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The outbreak (also known as **Golden Square outbreak**), which killed 616 people, is best known for the physician John Snow's study of its causes and his hypothesis that germ-contaminated water was the cause, rather than something in the air called "miasma".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This discovery influenced public health and the construction of improved sanitation facilities beginning in the mid-19th century.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Later, the term "focus of infection" was used to describe sites, such as the Broad Street pump, where conditions are favourable for transmission of infection.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow unknowingly took advantage of a natural experiment during his endeavours to identify the cause of cholera transmission.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In the mid-19th century, Soho in London had a serious problem with filth due to a large influx of people and lack of proper sanitary services: the London sewer system had not reached Soho.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cowsheds, slaughterhouses and grease-boiling dens lined the streets and contributed animal droppings, rotting fluids and other contaminants to Soho's primitive sewer system.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many cellars had cesspools beneath their floorboards, which formed from the sewers and filth seeping in from outside.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] With the cesspools overrunning, London's government decided to dump the waste into the River Thames, contaminating the water supply.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] London had already had a "series of debilitating cholera outbreaks".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] These included outbreaks in 1832 and 1849, which killed 14,137 people.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time of the Broad Street outbreak, physicians and scientists held two competing theories on the causes of cholera in the human body: miasma theory and germ theory.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London medical community debated the cause of the city's persistent cholera outbreaks.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera-causing bacterium *Vibrio cholerae* was isolated in 1854, but the finding became well known and accepted only decades later.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists concluded that cholera was caused by particles in the air, or "miasmata", which arose from decomposing matter or other dirty organic sources.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "Miasma" particles were thought to travel through the air and infect individuals, and thus cause cholera.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr William Farr, the commissioner for the 1851 London census and a member of the General Register's Office, believed that miasma arose from the soil surrounding the River Thames.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It contained decaying organic matter which contained miasmatic particles and was released into the London air.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Miasma theorists believed in "cleansing and scouring, rather than through the purer scientific approach of microbiology".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Farr later agreed with Snow's germ theory following Snow's publications.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In contrast, the germ theory held that the principal cause of cholera was a germ cell that had not yet been identified.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow theorised that this unknown germ was transmitted from person to person by individuals ingesting water.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] John Simon, a pathologist and London's lead medical officer, called Snow's germ theory "peculiar".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Even though Simon understood Snow's theory, he questioned its relation to the cause of cholera.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] On 31 August 1854, after several other outbreaks elsewhere in the city, there was a major outbreak of cholera in Soho.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Over the next three days, 127 people on or near Broad Street died.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the next week, three quarters of the residents had fled the area.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By 10 September, more than 500 people had died and the mortality rate was 12.8 per thousand inhabitants in some parts of the city.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By the end of the outbreak, 616 people had died.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Many of the victims were taken to the Middlesex Hospital, where their treatment was superintended by Florence Nightingale, who briefly joined the hospital in early September in order to help with the outbreak.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to a letter by Elizabeth Gaskell, Nightingale "was up night and day from Friday afternoon (Sept.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] 1) to Sunday afternoon, receiving the poor creatures (chiefly fallen women of that neighbourhood - they had it the worst) who were being constantly brought in - - undressing them - putting on turpentine stupes, et cetera, doing it herself to as many as she could manage".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] By talking to local residents (with the help of Reverend Henry Whitehead), Snow identified the outbreak's source as the public water pump on Broad Street (now Broadwick Street) at Cambridge Street.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Although Snow's chemical and microscope examination of a sample of the water from this Broad Street pump water did not conclusively prove its danger, the patterns of illness and death among residents in Soho persuaded the St James parish authorities to disable the pump by removing its handle.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow later used a dot map to illustrate how cases of cholera occurred around this pump.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] His efforts to connect the incidence of cholera with potential geographic sources was based on what is now known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He mapped the individual water pumps and generated cells representing all the points on his map that were closest to each pump.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The section of Snow's map representing areas in the city where the closest available source of water was the Broad Street pump had the highest incidence of cholera.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] There was one significant anomaly: none of the workers in the nearby Broad Street brewery contracted cholera.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As they were given a daily allowance of beer, they did not consume water from the nearby well.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] During the brewing process, the wort (un-fermented beer) is boiled in part so that hops can be added.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This step killed the cholera bacteria in the water they used to brew with, making it safe to drink.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow showed that the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company was taking water from sewage-polluted sections of the Thames and delivering it to homes, resulting in an increased incidence of cholera among its customers.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's study is part of the history of public health and health geography.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It is regarded as the founding event of epidemiology.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] It was discovered later that this public well had been dug 3 feet (0.9 m) from an old cesspit that had begun to leak faecal bacteria.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Waste water from washing nappies used by a baby who had contracted cholera from another source drained into this cesspit.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Its opening was under a nearby house that had been rebuilt further away after a fire and a street widening.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the time there were cesspits under most homes.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Most families tried to have their raw sewage collected and dumped in the Thames to prevent their cesspit from filling faster than the sewage could decompose into the soil.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] At the same time, an investigation of cholera transmission was being conducted in Deptford.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Around 90 people died within a few days in that town, where the water was known to be clean, and there had been no previous outbreaks of cholera.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was informed that the water had recently turned impure.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Before using it, residents had to let it run until the sudsy, sewer-like water turned clear.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow, finding that the water the residents were using was no different from the usual water from their pump, determined that the outbreak must be caused by a leak in the pipes that allowed surrounding sewage and its contaminants to seep in to the water supply.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] This was similar to the Broad Street outbreak.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The incoming water was being contaminated by the increasing levels of sewage, coupled with lack of safe plumbing.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] After the cholera epidemic subsided, government officials replaced the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They had responded only to the urgent threat posed to the population, and afterwards they rejected Snow's theory.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] To accept his proposal would have meant indirectly accepting the oral-faecal method of transmission of disease, which was too unpleasant for most of the public to contemplate.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Broad Street outbreak was an effect rather than a cause of the epidemic.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's conclusions were not predominantly based on the Broad Street outbreak, as he noted that he hesitated to come to a conclusion based on a population that had predominantly fled the neighbourhood and redistributed itself.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He feared throwing off results of the study.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] From a mathematical perspective, Snow's innovation was focusing on death rates in areas served by two water companies that drew water from the Thames, rather than basing it on data from victims of the Broad Street pump (which drew water from a well).
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work also led to a far greater health and safety impact than the removal of the Broad Street pump handle.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Deactivating the pump "hardly made a dent in the citywide cholera epidemic, which went on to claim nearly 3,000 lives".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow was sceptical of the prevailing miasma theory, which held that diseases such as cholera or the Black Death were caused by pollution or a noxious form of "bad air".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The germ theory was not yet established (Louis Pasteur proposed it in 1861).
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow did not understand the mechanism by which disease was transmitted, but the evidence led him to believe that it was not foul air.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Based on the pattern of illness among residents, he hypothesized that cholera was spread by an agent in contaminated water.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He first published his theory in 1849, in an essay titled "On the Mode of Communication of Cholera".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1855 he published a second edition, including a more elaborate investigation of the effect of the water supply in the 1854 Soho outbreak.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The cholera epidemic of 1849–1854 was also related to the water supplied by companies in London at the time.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The main players were the Southwark and Vauxhall Waterworks Company and the Lambeth Waterworks Company.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Both provided water to their customers drawn from the Thames, which was highly contaminated with visible and invisible products and bacteria.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Arthur Hill Hassall examined the filtered water and found it contained animal hair, among other foul substances.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Other companies, such as the New River Company and Chelsea Waterworks Company, were observed to have better filtered water; few deaths occurred in the neighbourhoods they supplied.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They not only obtained their water from cleaner sources than the Thames, but filtered the water and treated it until there were no obvious contaminants.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As mentioned above, Snow is known for his influence on public health, which arose after his studies of the cholera epidemic.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In attempting to figure out who was receiving impure water in each neighbourhood, what is now known as a double-blind experiment fell right into his lap.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow went on to study the water contents from each home through a test performed on each sample.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In this way, it could be deduced from which supplier the home received its water.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that it was indeed impure water from the big companies that allowed cholera to spread rapidly.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He proved this by observing London prisons, finding that cholera ceased there only a few days after switching to cleaner water sources.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's analysis of cholera and cholera outbreaks extended past the closure of the Broad Street pump.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He concluded that cholera was transmitted through and affected the alimentary canal within the human body.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Cholera did not affect either the circulatory or the nervous system and there was no "poison in the blood...in the consecutive fever...the blood became poisoned from urea getting into the circulation".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, this "urea" entered the blood through kidney failure.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Therefore, the fever was caused by kidney failure, not by a poison already present in the subject's bloodstream.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Popular medical practices, such as bloodletting, could not be effective in such a case.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow also argued that cholera was not a product of Miasma.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] "There was nothing in the air to account for the spread of cholera".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] According to Snow, cholera was spread by persons ingesting a substance, not through atmospheric transmittal.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Reverend Henry Whitehead was an assistant curate at St.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Luke's church in Soho during the 1854 cholera outbreak.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A former believer in the miasma theory of disease, Whitehead worked to disprove false theories.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was influenced by Snow's theory that cholera spreads by consumption of water contaminated by human waste.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Snow's work, particularly his maps of the Soho area cholera victims, convinced Whitehead that the Broad Street pump was the source of the local infections.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead joined Snow in tracking the contamination to a faulty cesspool and the outbreak's index case (the baby with cholera).
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Whitehead's work with Snow combined demographic study with scientific observation, setting an important precedent for epidemiology.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The London Board of Health, which had recently been given new powers and was presided over by Sir Benjamin Hall, a Cabinet Minister, had several committees, of which the Committee for Scientific Inquiries was placed in charge of investigating the cholera outbreak.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] They were to study the atmospheric environment in London and to examine samples of water from several London water companies.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The committee found that the most contaminated water supply came from the South London water companies, Southwark and Vauxhall.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of the Committee for Scientific Inquiries, Richard Dundas Thomson and Arthur Hill Hassall examined what Thomson called "vibriones".
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Thomson examined the occurrence of vibriones in air samples from various cholera wards and Hassall observed vibriones in water samples.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Neither identified vibriones as the cause of cholera.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] As part of its investigation of the cholera epidemic, the Board of Health sent physicians to examine in detail the conditions of the Golden Square neighbourhood and its inhabitants.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The Board of Health ultimately attributed the 1854 epidemic to miasma.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Dr Edwin Lankester was a physician on the local research conglomerate that studied the 1854 Broad Street cholera epidemic.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] In 1866, Lankester wrote about Snow's conclusion that the pump caused the outbreak.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He agreed with Snow at the time, but his opinion, like Snow's, was not publicly supported.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Lankester subsequently closed the pump due to Snow's theory and data on the pattern of infection, and infection rates dropped significantly.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] He was eventually named the first medical officer of health for St James's parish in London, the area where the pump was.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] A replica pump was installed in 1992 at the site of the 1854 pump.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Every year the John Snow Society holds "Pumphandle Lectures" on public health subjects.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] Until 2015, when the pump was removed due to redevelopment, it also held a ceremony there in which it removed and reattached the pump handle to commemorate Snow's discovery.
[src:london/1854-broad-street-cholera-outbreak] The pump's original location is marked by a red granite paver, and plaques at the John Snow pub at the corner describe Snow's findings.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:london/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:london/london-p01] As one of the world's major global cities, London exerts a strong influence on world art, architecture, culture, cinema, entertainment, commerce, finance, education, healthcare, media, science, technology, tourism, transport and communications.
[src:london/london-p01] London is Europe's largest city economy and one of the world's major financial centres.
[src:london/london-p01] London is home to several of the world's leading academic institutions and hosts Europe's largest concentration of higher education institutions, comprising over 50 universities and colleges collectively enrolling more than 500,000 students in 2023.
[src:london/london-p01] It is the most-visited city in Europe and has the world's busiest city airport system.
[src:london/london-p01] The London Underground is the world's oldest rapid transit system.
[src:london/london-p01] London's diverse cultures encompass over 300 languages.
[src:london/london-p01] The 2025 population of Greater London of just over 9.8 million made it Europe's third-most populous city, accounting for 13.1 per cent of the United Kingdom's population and 15.5 per cent of England's population.
[src:london/london-p01] The Greater London Built-up Area is the fourth-most populous in Europe, with about 9.8 million inhabitants as of 2011.
[src:london/london-p01] The London metropolitan area is the third-most-populous in Europe, with about 15 million inhabitants as of 2025, making London a megacity.
[src:london/london-p01] Landmarks include the Tower of London, Westminster Abbey, Buckingham Palace, the London Eye, Piccadilly Circus, St Paul's Cathedral, Tower Bridge and Trafalgar Square.
[src:london/london-p01] The city has the most museums, art galleries, libraries and cultural venues in the UK, including the British Museum, the National Gallery, the Natural History Museum, Tate Modern, the British Library and numerous West End theatres.
[src:london/london-p01] Annual sporting events include the FA Cup Final (held at Wembley Stadium), the Wimbledon Tennis Championships and the London Marathon.
[src:london/london-p01] It became the first city to host three Summer Olympic Games upon hosting the 2012 Summer Olympics after previously hosting in 1908 and 1948.
[src:london/london-p01] The name *London* is attested in the first century AD, usually in the Latinised form *Londinium*.
[src:london/london-p01] Modern scientific analyses of the name must account for the origins of the different forms that are found in early sources, such as Latin *Londinium*, Old English *Lunden*, and Welsh *Llundein*, with reference to the known developments over time of sounds in those different languages.
[src:london/london-p01] The name came into these languages from Common Brythonic; the lost Celtic form of the name was most likely **Londonjon*.
[src:london/london-p01] Until 1889, the name "London" applied officially only to the City of London, but since then it has also denoted the County of London and Greater London.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1993 remains of a Bronze Age bridge were found on the south River Thames foreshore, upstream from Vauxhall Bridge.
[src:london/london-p01] Two of the timbers were radiocarbon dated to 1750–1285 BC.
[src:london/london-p01] In 2010 foundations of a large timber structure, dated to 4800–4500 BC, were found on the Thames' south foreshore downstream from Vauxhall Bridge.
[src:london/london-p01] Both are on the south bank of the Thames, where the now-underground River Effra flows into the Thames.
[src:london/london-p01] Despite the evidence of scattered Brythonic settlements in the area, the first major settlement was founded by the Romans around AD 47, about 4 years after their invasion of AD 43.
[src:london/london-p01] This only lasted until about AD 61, when the Iceni tribe led by Queen Boudica stormed it and burnt it to the ground.
[src:london/london-p01] The next planned incarnation of Londinium prospered, superseding Colchester as the principal city of the Roman province of Britannia in 100.
[src:london/london-p01] At its height in the 2nd century, Roman London had a population of about 60,000.
[src:london/london-p01] With the early-5th-century collapse of Roman rule, the walled city of Londinium was effectively abandoned, although Roman civilisation continued around St Martin-in-the-Fields until about 450.
[src:london/london-p01] From about 500 an Anglo-Saxon settlement known as Lundenwic developed slightly west of the old Roman city.
[src:london/london-p01] By about 680 the city had become a major port again, but there is little evidence of large-scale production.
[src:london/london-p01] From the 820s repeated Viking assaults brought decline.
[src:london/london-p01] The Vikings applied Danelaw over much of eastern and northern England from 886; The *Anglo-Saxon Chronicle* records that Alfred "refounded" London that year.
[src:london/london-p01] This involved the abandonment of Lundenwic and a revival of life and trade within the old Roman walls.
[src:london/london-p01] London then grew slowly until a dramatic increase in about 950.
[src:london/london-p01] By the 11th century, London was clearly the largest town in England.
[src:london/london-p01] Westminster Abbey, rebuilt in Romanesque style by King Edward the Confessor, was one of the grandest churches in Europe.
[src:london/london-p01] Winchester had been the capital of Anglo-Saxon England, but from this time, London became the main forum for foreign traders and the base for defence in time of war.
[src:london/london-p01] After winning the Battle of Hastings, William, Duke of Normandy, was crowned King of England as William I in the newly completed Westminster Abbey on Christmas Day 1066.
[src:london/london-p01] He built the Tower of London to intimidate the inhabitants.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1097 William II began building Westminster Hall, near the abbey.
[src:london/london-p01] It became the basis of a new Palace of Westminster.
[src:london/london-p01] In the 12th century the institutions of central government, which had followed the royal English court around the country, grew in size and sophistication and became increasingly fixed, for most purposes at Westminster, although the royal treasury came to rest in the Tower of London.
[src:london/london-p01] While the City of Westminster developed into a true governmental capital, its distinct neighbour, the City of London, remained England's largest city and principal commercial centre and flourished under its own unique administration, the Corporation of London.
[src:london/london-p01] With the Black Death in the mid-14th century, London lost nearly a third of its population.
[src:london/london-p01] London was the focus of the Peasants' Revolt in 1381.
[src:london/london-p01] London was a centre of England's Jewish population before their expulsion by Edward I in 1290.
[src:london/london-p01] Violence against Jews occurred in 1190, when it was rumoured that Richard I had ordered their massacre after some of their leaders had presented themselves at his coronation.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1264, during the Second Barons' War, Simon de Montfort's rebels killed 500 Jews while attempting to seize records of debts.
[src:london/london-p01] The Reformation produced a shift to Protestantism.
[src:london/london-p01] Much property passed into private ownership, accelerating business in the city.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1475 the Hanseatic League set up a trading base.
[src:london/london-p01] Woollen cloth was shipped undyed from 14th- and 15th-century London to the Low Countries.
[src:london/london-p01] The reopening of the Netherlands to English shipping in January 1565 spurred a burst of commercial activity.
[src:london/london-p01] Mercantilism grew and monopoly traders such as the East India Company were founded as trade expanded to the New World.
[src:london/london-p01] London became the main North Sea port, with migrants from England and abroad.
[src:london/london-p01] Shakespeare built his Globe Theatre in Southwark in 1599.
[src:london/london-p01] Stage performances halted when Puritan authorities shut down the theatres in the 1640s.
[src:london/london-p01] The ban was lifted during the 1660 Restoration; London's oldest theatre, Drury Lane, opened in 1663.
[src:london/london-p01] By the end of the Tudor period in 1603, London was still compact.
[src:london/london-p01] There was an assassination attempt on James I in Westminster, in the Gunpowder Plot of 5 November 1605.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1637 the government of Charles I attempted to reform London's administration; the Corporation made "The Great Refusal", explaining the City of London's unique governmental status.
[src:london/london-p01] In the English Civil War, most Londoners supported the Roundheads.
[src:london/london-p01] After an advance by the Cavaliers in 1642, culminating in the battles of Brentford and Turnham Green, London was surrounded by a defensive perimeter wall.
[src:london/london-p01] The fortifications failed their only test when the New Model Army entered London in 1647.
[src:london/london-p01] London suffered the Great Plague of 1665–1666, killing some 100,000 people, a fifth of the population.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1666, the Great Fire destroyed much of the wooden-built city.
[src:london/london-p01] Rebuilding took over 10 years, supervised by the polymath Robert Hooke.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1710, Christopher Wren's masterpiece St Paul's Cathedral was completed, replacing its medieval predecessor, lost in the Great Fire.
[src:london/london-p01] Its dome dominated the London skyline for centuries, inspiring William Blake, whose 1789 poem "Holy Thursday" mentions 'the high dome of Pauls'.
[src:london/london-p01] During the Georgian era new districts such as Mayfair were formed in the west, while new bridges encouraged development in South London.
[src:london/london-p01] In the east, the Port of London expanded downstream, while the financial centre matured.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1762 George III acquired Buckingham House.
[src:london/london-p01] During the 18th century London was dogged by crime, and the Bow Street Runners were established in 1750 as a professional police force.
[src:london/london-p01] Epidemics during the 1720s and 30s saw most children born in the city die before reaching their fifth birthday.
[src:london/london-p01] Growing literacy and printed papers made news widely available; Fleet Street became the centre of the British press, and Londoners debated in coffeehouses.
[src:london/london-p01] Napoleon's invasion of Amsterdam led many financiers to relocate to London and the first London international issue was arranged in 1817.
[src:london/london-p01] The Royal Navy became the world's leading war fleet, acting as a deterrent to economic adversaries.
[src:london/london-p01] Following an 1838 fire, the Royal Exchange was rebuilt in 1844.
[src:london/london-p01] The 1846 repeal of the Corn Laws, meant to weaken Dutch economic power, enabled London to overtake Amsterdam as the leading international financial centre.
[src:london/london-p01] The Industrial Revolution saw unprecedented urbanisation.
[src:london/london-p01] London was the world's largest city from about 1831 to 1925, with a population density of 132 per acre (325 per hectare).
[src:london/london-p01] Harding, Howell & Co. on Pall Mall was one of the first department stores, alongside many street sellers.
[src:london/london-p01] The London Underground, the world's first urban rail network, was created in response to traffic congestion.
[src:london/london-p01] Overcrowding led to cholera epidemics, claiming 14,000 lives in 1848, and 6,000 in 1866.
[src:london/london-p01] A modern sewage system was created by the Metropolitan Board of Works; it diverted waste to the Thames Estuary, and by the 1890s used biological treatment of sewage to oxidise the waste.
[src:london/london-p01] The Metropolitan Board of Works oversaw infrastructure expansion in the capital and some surrounding counties.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1894, Lyons opened their first chain of teashops in Piccadilly.
[src:london/london-p01] Tearooms became popular meeting places for women from the suffrage movement.
[src:london/london-p01] Westminster Abbey and St Paul's Cathedral were bombed in the 1912–14 suffragette bombing and arson campaign.
[src:london/london-p01] London was bombed by the Germans in the First World War.
[src:london/london-p01] During the Second World War, the Blitz killed over 30,000 Londoners, destroying many buildings.
[src:london/london-p01] The tomb of the Unknown Warrior was created in Westminster Abbey on 11 November 1920 and The Cenotaph, in Whitehall, was unveiled on the same day; it is the focus the National Service of Remembrance held annually on Remembrance Sunday.
[src:london/london-p01] The 1948 Summer Olympics were held at the original Wembley Stadium, while London was still recovering from the war.
[src:london/london-p01] From the 1940s, London became home to many immigrants, primarily from Commonwealth countries such as Jamaica, India, Bangladesh and Pakistan, making London one of the most multiracial cities in the world.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1951 the Festival of Britain was held on the South Bank.
[src:london/london-p01] The Great Smog of 1952 led to the Clean Air Act 1956, which ended the "pea soup fogs" which had earned London the nickname the "Big Smoke".
[src:london/london-p01] In the mid-1960s, London became a centre for worldwide youth culture, exemplified by the Swinging London sub-culture of the King's Road, Chelsea and Carnaby Street.
[src:london/london-p01] The role of trendsetter revived in the punk era.
[src:london/london-p01] In 1965 London's political boundaries were expanded in response to the city's growth, and a new Greater London Council was created.
[src:london/london-p01] During the Troubles in Northern Ireland, London was hit from 1973 by bomb attacks by the Provisional Irish Republican Army.
[src:london/london-p01] These attacks lasted for two decades, starting with the Old Bailey bombing.
[src:london/london-p01] Greater London's population declined after the Second World War, from an estimated peak of 8.6 million in 1939 to around 6.8 million in the 1980s.
[src:london/london-p01] By January 2015 Greater London's population had increased again to 8.63 million.
[src:london/london-p01] The principal ports for London moved downstream to Felixstowe and Tilbury, with the London Docklands area becoming a focus for regeneration.
[src:london/london-p01] 2 miles (3.2 km) east of central London, the Thames Barrier was completed in 1982 to protect London against tidal surges from the North Sea.
[src:london/london-p01] The Greater London Council was abolished in 1986, leaving London with no central administration until the creation of the Greater London Authority in 2000.
[src:london/london-p01] To mark the 21st century the Millennium Dome, the London Eye and the Millennium Bridge were constructed.
[src:london/london-p01] On 7 July 2005, three London Underground trains and a double-decker bus were bombed in a series of terrorist attacks.
[src:london/london-p01] In 2008 *Time* magazine hailed London as one of the world's three most influential global cities.
[src:london/london-p01] In terms of international connectedness, as of 2024, London was one of two cities worldwide classified as an "Alpha++" city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:london/london-p01] The administration of London is formed of two tiers: a citywide, strategic tier coordinated by the Greater London Authority (GLA), and a local tier with 33 local administrations.
[src:london/london-p01] The GLA consists of the mayor of London, who has executive powers, and the London Assembly, which scrutinises the mayor's decisions and can accept or reject the mayor's annual budget proposals.
[src:london/london-p01] The GLA is responsible for most of London's transport system through Transport for London (TfL), overseeing the city's police and fire services, and setting a strategic vision for London.
[src:london/london-p01] The headquarters of the GLA is City Hall in Newham.
[src:london/london-p01] The local authorities are the councils of the 32 London boroughs and the City of London Corporation.
[src:london/london-p01] They are responsible for most local services, including local planning, schools, libraries, leisure and recreation, social services, local roads and refuse collection.
[src:london/london-p01] Some functions, such as waste management, are provided through joint arrangements.
[src:london/london-p01] In 2009–2010 the revenue expenditure by London councils and the GLA amounted to just over £22 billion (£14.7 billion for the boroughs and £7.4 billion for the GLA).
[src:london/london-p01] The London Fire Brigade is the statutory fire and rescue service for Greater London, run by the London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority.
[src:london/london-p01] National Health Service ambulance services are provided by the London Ambulance Service (LAS) NHS Trust.
[src:london/london-p01] The London Air Ambulance charity operates in conjunction with the LAS where required.
[src:london/london-p01] His Majesty's Coastguard and the Royal National Lifeboat Institution operate on the River Thames, under the jurisdiction of the Port of London Authority from Teddington Lock to the sea.
[src:london/london-p01] Policing in Greater London, with the exception of the City of London, is provided by the Metropolitan Police ("The Met"), overseen by the mayor through the Mayor's Office for Policing and Crime.
[src:london/london-p01] The British Transport Police are responsible for police services on National Rail, London Underground, Docklands Light Railway and Tramlink services.
[src:london/london-p01] The Ministry of Defence Police is a specialised police force in London.
[src:london/london-p01] London is the seat of the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:london/london-p01] Many government departments and the prime minister's residence at 10 Downing Street are based close to the Palace of Westminster, particularly along Whitehall.
[src:london/london-p01] There are 75 members of Parliament from London; as at June 2024, 59 are from the Labour Party, 9 are Conservatives, 6 are Liberal Democrats and one constituency is held by an independent.
[src:london/london-p01] The ministerial post of Minister for London was created in 1994; it has been vacant since July 2024.
[src:london/london-p01] Greater London is one of nine regions of England and the top subdivision covering most of the metropolis.
[src:london/london-p01] The City of London at its core once comprised the whole settlement; as its urban area grew, the Corporation of London resisted attempts to amalgamate the city with its suburbs, causing "London" to be defined several ways.
[src:london/london-p01] Forty per cent of Greater London is covered by the London post town, in which "London" forms part of postal addresses.
[src:london/london-p01] The London telephone area code (020) covers an area similar in size to Greater London, although some outer districts are excluded and some just outside included.
[src:london/london-p01] The London linked-number area extends 18 miles around Kings Cross, see Director telephone system.
[src:london/london-p01] The Greater London boundary has been aligned to the M25 motorway in places.
[src:london/london-p01] Urban expansion is prevented by the Metropolitan Green Belt, although the built-up area extends beyond the boundary in places, producing a separately defined Greater London Urban Area.
[src:london/london-p01] Beyond this is the London commuter belt.
[src:london/london-p01] Greater London is split for some purposes into Inner London and Outer London, and by the River Thames into North and South, with an informal Central London area.
[src:london/london-p01] The coordinates of the nominal "centre of London", traditionally the original Eleanor Cross at Charing Cross near the junction of Trafalgar Square and Whitehall, are about 51°30′26″N 00°07′39″W﻿ / ﻿51.50722°N 0.12750°W﻿ / 51.50722; -0.12750.
[src:london/london-p01] Within London, the City of London and the City of Westminster have city status.
[src:london/london-p01] The City of London and the remainder of Greater London are ceremonial counties.
[src:london/london-p01] Greater London includes parts of the historic counties of Middlesex, Kent, Surrey, Essex and Hertfordshire.
[src:london/london-p01] Greater London has been defined as a region of England.
[src:london/london-p01] London is the capital of the United Kingdom and of England by convention.
[src:london/london-p01] The capital of England was moved from Winchester as the Palace of Westminster developed in the 12th and 13th centuries to become the home of the royal court, and thus the nation's political capital.
[src:london/london-p01] Greater London has an area of 611 square miles (1,583 km2), while the London Metropolitan Region has an area of 3,236 square miles (8,382 km2).
[src:london/london-p01] Modern London stands on the Thames, its primary geographical feature, a navigable river which crosses the city from the south-west to the east.
[src:london/london-p01] The Thames Valley is a flood plain surrounded by gently rolling hills including Parliament Hill, Addington Hills, and Primrose Hill.
[src:london/london-p01] Historically, London grew up at the river's lowest bridging point.
[src:london/london-p01] The Thames was once much broader and shallower with extensive wetlands; at high tide, its shores reached five times their present width.
[src:london/london-p01] Since the Victorian era the Thames has been embanked, and many of its London tributaries now flow underground.
[src:london/london-p01] The Thames is tidal, and London is vulnerable to flooding.
[src:london/london-p01] The threat has increased because of a continuous rise in high water level caused by climate change and by the slow 'tilting' of the British Isles through post-glacial rebound.
[src:london/london-p01] London has a temperate oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*).
[src:london/london-p01] The average annual precipitation is about 600 mm (24 in).
[src:london/london-p01] Despite relatively low annual precipitation, London receives 109.6 rainy days on the 1 mm (0.039 in) threshold annually.
[src:london/london-p01] London is vulnerable to climate change, and experts are concerned that households may run out of water before 2050.
[src:london/london-p01] Summers are generally warm, sometimes hot.
[src:london/london-p01] On average each year, London experiences 31 days above 25 °C (77.0 °F) and 4.2 days above 30.0 °C (86.0 °F).
[src:london/london-p01] Winters are generally cool with little temperature variation.
[src:london/london-p01] Heavy snow is rare, but snow usually falls at least once each winter.
[src:london/london-p01] As a large city, London has a considerable urban heat island effect, making the centre of London at times 5 °C (9 °F) warmer than the suburbs and outskirts.
[src:london/london-p01] See Climate of London for additional climate information.
[src:london/london-p01] Places within London are identified using area names, such as Mayfair, Southwark, and Whitechapel.
[src:london/london-p01] These are informal designations, reflect the names of villages that have been absorbed by sprawl, or are superseded administrative units.
[src:london/london-p01] Since 1965, Greater London has been divided into 32 London boroughs in addition to its once walled ancient core, the City of London.
[src:london/london-p01] The City of London is the main financial district, and Canary Wharf has developed into a new financial and commercial hub in the Docklands.
